{"title_page": "Battle of Tripoli Airport", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Tripoli Airport\n|partof=the [[2014 Libyan conflict]]\n| image= Tripoli Airport.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=Tripoli International Airport\n|date=13 July \u2013 23 August 2014<br>({{Age in months, weeks and days|month1=07|day1=13|year1=2014|month2=08|day2=23|year2=2014}})\n|place=[[Tripoli International Airport]], [[Libya]]\n|territory=\n|result=Libya Dawn victory\n*[[Zintan]]i forces and their allies withdraw on orders of [[House of Representatives (Libya)|House of Representatives]]\n*Islamist armed groups take control of the airport\n*Airport now unused\n|combatants_header=Belligerents<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/security/2014/08/libya-tripoli-control-hifter-tribal-forces.html | title=Dawn of Libya forces impose control on Tripoli | publisher=Al-Monitor | date=August 25, 2014 | accessdate=August 27, 2014 | author=Daleh, Mustafa}}</ref>\n|combatant1={{Flagicon|Libya}} [[Zintan Brigade|Zintani brigades]]\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}} Al-Qaqa battalion\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}} Al Sawa'iq battalion\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}} Warshefana battalions\n*Zintani Airport Security\n----\n'''Supported by:'''\n*{{flag|Egypt}}<ref name=\"egyptuae\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/26/world/africa/egypt-and-united-arab-emirates-said-to-have-secretly-carried-out-libya-airstrikes.html | title=Egypt and United Arab Emirates Said to Have Secretly Carried Out Libya Airstrikes | publisher=The New York Times | date=August 25, 2014 | accessdate=August 25, 2014 | author=[[David D. Kirkpatrick|D. Kirkpatrick, David]] |author2=Schmitt, Eric}}</ref><ref>http://www.libyaherald.com/2014/08/28/egypt-prepared-to-take-lead-in-ensuring-stability-in-libya/</ref>\n*{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}<ref name=\"egyptuae\"/>\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Libyan National Army]]\n\n|combatant2={{Flagicon|Libya}} Libya Dawn coalition\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Libya Revolutionaries Operations Room]]\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Libya Shield Force|Central Shield]] Misrata brigades\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Al Somoud Battalion]] \n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Ghnewa Al Kikli Battalion]]\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Al Qabra Battalion]]\n*[[File:Flag of Jihad.svg|25px]][[Ansar al-Sharia (Libya)]]\n\n----\n'''Supported by:'''\n*{{flag|Qatar}}<ref name=\"egyptuae\"/>\n*{{flag|Turkey}}\n\n|commander1=\n|commander2={{Flagicon|Libya}} [[Nouri Abusahmain]]<br>([[List of heads of state of Libya|President of the GNC]], disputed)<br>\n{{Flagicon|Libya}} [[Sadiq Al-Ghariani]]<br>([[Grand Mufti]])<br>\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Libya.svg}} [[Mohammed Hadia]]<br>(Operation Libya Dawn Commander)<br>\n{{Flagicon image|<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: Flag of the Joint Operations Room of Libya\u2019s Revolutionaries.svg -->}}  [[Shaaban Hadia]]<br>(LROR Commander)\n|strength1=\n|strength2=\n|casualties3=\n|notes=\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox 2014 Libyan Civil War}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Tripoli Airport''' was a battle of the [[Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|Libyan Civil War]]. It began on 13 July 2014 as part of the \"[[Libya Dawn]]\" Coalition operation and ended in August 2014. The battle was fought between a [[Islamist]] [[New General National Congress]] coalition and the [[Zintan Brigade|Zintani brigades]].\n\n==Background==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Tripoli (June 15 2014).png|thumb|left|Situation in Tripoli mid June 2014; airport is further south]]\nThe Zintani Brigades had provided security for Tripoli International Airport since the 2011 War which overthrew [[Gadhafi]].\n\nAfter the defeat of Islamist politicians in the [[2014 Libyan parliamentary election]], the [[Libya Revolutionaries Operations Room]] and [[Misrata Brigades]] were faced with a largely anti-Islamist [[House of Representatives (Libya)|parliament]]. Their most powerful political ally, [[Nouri Abusahmain]], was faced with an imminent loss of power, and they were likely to lose funding from the [[General National Congress]]. The anti-Islamist politicians who won the 2014 elections had previously tried to disband the Libya Revolutionaries Operations Room due to its attempted coup in 2013, and were able to do so after the election results.\n\n==Combatants==\nThe New General National Congress coalition, dubbed operation [[Libya Dawn]] was composed of the [[Libya Revolutionaries Operations Room]] included the following groups:\n*[[Misrata battalion|Misrata's]] Al Somood batallion led by Salah Badi<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya airport takeover widens political split |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/08/libya-airport-takeover-tripoli-political-split-20148249154577648.html |website=Aljazeera English |publisher=Aljazeera English News - 24 Aug 2014 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Military leader that burned Tripoli airport of the capital of Libya to cleanse it from \"Corruption\". |url=https://elqalamcenter.com/2018/08/29/\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0626\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0633\u0643\u0631\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a-\u0623\u062d\u0631\u0642-\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633-\u064a/ |website=Al-Qalam Center for Research and Studies |publisher=Al-Qalam Center for Research and Studies |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tripoli is Again Without an Airport Since Salah Badi\u2019s 2014 Attack |url=https://almarsad.co/en/2019/09/02/tripoli-is-again-without-an-airport-since-salah-badis-2014-attack/ |website=Almarsad.co |publisher=Almarsad news |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Ghnewa battalion]] led by Abdul Ghani Al-Kikli<ref>{{cite web |last1=Arfaoui |first1=Jamel |title=Who is Abdulghani Al Kikli? |url=https://tunisie-telegraph.com/2014/07/29/\u062a\u0648\u0631\u0637-\u0641\u064a-\u062d\u0631\u064a\u0642-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633-\u0648\u062c\u0627\u0621-\u0644\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u062c-\u0641\u064a-\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0633-4434 |website=Tunisie Telegraph (Tunisian Telegraph) |publisher=Tunisie Telegraph 29-07-2014 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=5 points of information you didnt know about Ghnewa Al Kikli |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/5-\u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645\u0627\u062a-\u0642\u062f-\u0644\u0627-\u062a\u0639\u0631\u0641\u0647\u0627-\u0639\u0646-\u063a\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0643\u0644\u064a/ |website=Afrigatenews.net |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=All you need to know about \"Operation Dawn of Libya\" |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0643\u0644-\u0645\u0627-\u062a\u0631\u064a\u062f-\u0623\u0646-\u062a\u0639\u0631\u0641\u0647-\u0639\u0646-\u0639\u0645\u0644\u064a\u0629-\u0641\u062c\u0631-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627/ |website=AfrigateNews.net - Africa news portal |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>, \n*Al-Qabra battalion led by Suleiman Al Shatwan.<ref>{{cite web |title=All you need to know about \"Operation Dawn of Libya\" |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0643\u0644-\u0645\u0627-\u062a\u0631\u064a\u062f-\u0623\u0646-\u062a\u0639\u0631\u0641\u0647-\u0639\u0646-\u0639\u0645\u0644\u064a\u0629-\u0641\u062c\u0631-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627/ |website=Afrigate News |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Misrata leader in the Misrata battalion killed in Tripoli airport clashes |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0645\u0642\u062a\u0644-\u0642\u064a\u0627\u062f\u064a-\u0641\u064a-\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0626\u0628-\u0645\u0635\u0631\u0627\u062a\u0629-\u0641\u064a-\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0643\u0627\u062a-\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633/ |website=AfrigateNews.net |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Supported by Qatari and Turkish military training, Intelligence and arms support<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkey, Qatar accused of delivering weapons to Libyan militants |url=https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/2/7972/Turkey-Qatar-accused-of-delivering-weapons-to-Libyan-militants |website=Egypt Today |publisher=Egypt Today, Sat, Jun. 17, 2017 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=United nations Security council report S/2014/106 |journal=UN Security Council report S/2014/106 |date=19 February 2014 |issue=S/2014/106 |pages=20/97  (67.) |url=https://www.securitycouncilreport.org/atf/cf/%7B65BFCF9B-6D27-4E9C-8CD3-CF6E4FF96FF9%7D/s_2014_106.pdf |accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref=67. Greece confirmed that the ship arrived in Volos on 24 January 2013 from Derince, Turkey.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Death Ships: The Chronology of Turkish Weapons Ships to Libya |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0633\u0641\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u062a-\u0643\u0631\u0646\u0648\u0644\u0648\u062c\u064a\u0627-\u0633\u0641\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u0644\u062d\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0643\u064a\u0629-\u0625\u0644\u0649-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627/ |website=AfrigateNews.net |publisher=Afrigate News |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wehrey |first1=Frederic |title=Is Libya a proxy war? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2014/10/24/is-libya-a-proxy-war/ |website=Washington Post |publisher=Washington Post October 24, 2014 at 5:00 PM EDT |accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref=\", with their respective special forces supporting disparate revolutionary factions with intelligence, training and arms. \"}}</ref>. \n\nThe Zintani-led brigades consisted of the following groups: \n*Al-Qaqa battallion<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya, Militias burn down Tripoli airport after capturing it. |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/north-africa/libya/2014/08/24/\u0627\u0644\u0635\u0648\u0631-\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644\u0649-\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0642-\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633-\u0639\u0644\u0649-\u064a\u062f-\u0645\u064a\u0644\u064a\u0634\u064a\u0627\u062a-\u0645\u062a\u0637\u0631\u0641\u0629 |website=Al Arabiya |publisher=Al Arabiya |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> led by Maj.Gen. Othman Al Mulaitaqa<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya Qaqaa Batalion, Defending Tripoli from Hostiles |url=https://aawsat.com/home/article/41516 |website=Al Sharq Alwast |publisher=AlSharq-Alwast, aawsat.com/ |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Libyan militias withdraw from the capital, Tripoli |url=https://www.bbc.com/arabic/middleeast/2013/11/131121_libya_militias_withdraw_from_tripoli |website=BBC news Arabic |publisher=BBC NEWS Arabic |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Al-Sawa'iq battalion<ref>{{cite book |title=Libya: Security Situation report |date=19 December 2014 |publisher=US Department of Justice website \"Justic.gov\" |pages=14 / 76 |ref=3.2.4 The Zintan battalion}}</ref> led by Imad Mustafa Traboulsi<ref>{{cite web |title=Discover 6 information about Emad Trabelsi |url=Https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0643\u062a\u0634\u0641-6-\u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645\u0627\u062a-\u0639\u0646-\u0639\u0645\u0627\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633\u064a/ |website=AfrigateNews.Net |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n*Members of [[:ar:\u0648\u0631\u0634\u0641\u0627\u0646\u0629|Warshefana]] battalions. \n*Received materiel and Air support from the [[Libyan National Army]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The Libyan National Army claims responsibility for bombing armed militants in Tripoli |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/north-africa/libya/2014/08/18/\u0637\u0627\u0626\u0631\u0627\u062a-\u062d\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629-\u0645\u062c\u0647\u0648\u0644\u0629-\u0641\u064a-\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0621-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0635\u0645\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0629 |website=Al Arabiya news |publisher=Al Arabiya News |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Conflicting accounts of Libyan Tripoli raids |url=ttps://www.aljazeera.net/news/arabic/2014/8/19/\u062a\u0636\u0627\u0631\u0628-\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0648\u0627\u064a\u0627\u062a-\u0628\u0634\u0623\u0646-\u063a\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0629 |website=Aljazeera Arabic |publisher=Aljazeera Arabic |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Unidentified aircraft bomb the \"Dawn of Libya\" forces in Tripoli |url=https://www.aljazeera.net/news/arabic/2014/8/18/\u0637\u0627\u0626\u0631\u0627\u062a-\u0645\u062c\u0647\u0648\u0644\u0629-\u062a\u0642\u0635\u0641-\u0642\u0648\u0627\u062a-\u0641\u062c\u0631-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627-\u0648\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0643\u0627\u062a-\u0628\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633 |website=Aljazeera News Arabic |publisher=Aljazeera Arabic |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n\nOn 13 July the Libya Dawn coalition launched their operation to seize the airport. Many aircraft were destroyed on the ground. The operation received public support from [[Grand Mufti]] [[Sadiq Al-Ghariani]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya\u2019s highest spiritual leader banned from UK over support of Islamists |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/30/libya-spiritual-leader-banned-uk-islamists |website=The Guardian |publisher=The guardian |accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref=\"Speaking from the UK via the Libyan television station Tanasuh, the radical cleric celebrated the violent capture of Tripoli by Islamist militia force Libya Dawn, and ordered a widening of the rebellion.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Radical Cleric Al-Ghariani: Rebel Leaders Are Corrupt And LPA Is \u201cA Lost Deal\u201d! |url=https://www.addresslibya.com/en/archives/30621 |website=The Libyan Adress |publisher=The Libyan Adress 19 July\u060c 2018 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mustafa |first1=Ajnadin |title=Grand Mufti again backs Libya Dawn operation, calls Zintanis and allies \u201ctraitors\u201d |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2014/08/21/grand-mufti-again-backs-libya-dawn-operation-calls-zintanis-and-allies-traitors/ |website=Libya Herald |publisher=Libya Herald |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\nOn 23 August 2014, Zintani forces withdrew from the airport. They claimed that they withdrew because they had been instructed to do so by the parliament. This was later confirmed by parliamentary sources.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn the immediate aftermath of the battle, large fires and plumes of smoke arose from 4 large kerosene fuel containers that were struck by rocket attacks,<ref>{{cite web |title=\" A fourth oil depot ignited near the Tripoli airport\" Arabic: \"\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0644 \u0645\u0633\u062a\u0648\u062f\u0639 \u0646\u0641\u0637 \u0631\u0627\u0628\u0639 \u0642\u0631\u0628 \u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633\" |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0644-\u0645\u0633\u062a\u0648\u062f\u0639-\u0646\u0641\u0637-\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0639-\u0642\u0631\u0628-\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633 |website=AfrigateNews.net |publisher=Afrigate News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fuel Tank Blaze Near Tripoli Airport 'Out of Control' |url=https://www.voanews.com/africa/fuel-tank-blaze-near-tripoli-airport-out-control |website=VOA News |publisher=Voice of America |accessdate=26 March 2020 |ref=July 28, 2014 02:45 AM}}</ref> polluting the surrounding grounds and the air quality.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amara |first1=Hani |title=Fuel tanks hit in clashes near Libyan airport |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security/fuel-tanks-hit-in-clashes-near-libyan-airport-idUSKBN0FS16U20140723 |website=Reuters News |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Roads infrastructure on the exterior of the airport facility was damaged as well as inside the airport with mortar explosions and shrapnel. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sim |first1=David |title=Libya: Burnt-out Planes Litter Runway as Battle for Tripoli Airport Continues [PHOTOS] |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/libya-burnt-out-planes-litter-runway-battle-tripoli-airport-continues-photos-1457750 |website=International Business Times |publisher=David Sim, International Business Times, July 22, 2014 13:22 BST |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Turkia |first1=Hamza |title=30 dead in Libya int'l airport attack (4) |url=http://en.people.cn/n/2014/0717/c90777-8756909-4.html |website=Peoples Daily Online |publisher=Peoples Daily, Xinhua/Hamza Turkia |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Residential areas near to the airport were also damaged in the fighting, as some residences were used in the fighting as firing positions by all involved parties. \nResidential areas surrounding the airport were also damaged during the battle, mostly from light weapons [[7.62x32]], heavy weapons damage from [[zsu-23-2]] projectiles, [[RPG-7]] and on rare occasions larger damage from [[T-72]] rounds. There have been reports of violations against civilians<ref>{{cite web |title=OVERVIEW OF VIOLATIONS OF INTERNATIONAL HUMAN RIGHTS AND HUMANITARIAN LAW DURING THE ONGOING VIOLENCE IN LIBYA 4 September 2014 |url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Countries/LY/OverviewViolationsLibya_UNSMIL_OHCHR_Sept04_en.pdf |website=Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights OHCHR & UNSMIL |publisher=OHCHR - UN 4 September 2014 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>, and [[BM-21 Grad|GRAD]] rocket systems being used on civilian residential areas, with civilians caught in the crossfire despite many of them being displaced.<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya: Spiraling Militia Attacks May Be War Crimes |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/09/08/libya-spiraling-militia-attacks-may-be-war-crimes |website=Human Rights watch |publisher=Human Rights watch |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tripoli airport 2.jpg|thumb|left|Fires burning at the customs building of Tripoli international Airport in 2014]]\nThe airport main reception and customs building succumbed to catastrophic fire damage after an intense assault was launched by Islamist Libya Dawn and Al Somood militias to capture the facility during the final days of the battle which resulted in the defending Zintani forces withdrawing from the airport.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leaded Video shows Salah Badi within Tripoli Airport on the day it was captured by Libya Dawn Forces. |url=https://almarsad.co/2016/11/07/\u0641\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0648-\u0645\u0633\u0631\u0628-\u064a\u0638\u0647\u0631-\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d-\u0628\u0627\u062f\u064a-\u062f\u0627\u062e\u0644-\u0645\u0628\u0646\u0649-\u0645\u0637\u0627/ |website=Almarsad.co |publisher=AlMarsad.co |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>.\nThe entirety of the interior of the reception building that housed offices and processing areas, containing flammable materials completely burned off, rendering the mail building unusable.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Masdar News |first1=Masdar news |title=\"First pictures of the burning of the Airport caused by Extremists\" \" \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644\u0649 \u0644\u062d\u0631\u0642 \u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u064a\u062f \u0645\u064a\u0644\u064a\u0634\u064a\u0627\u062a \u0645\u062a\u0637\u0631\u0641\u0629\" |url=https://www.almasdar.com/2352 |website=Al-Masdar |publisher=AL Masdar News |accessdate=26 March 2020 |ref=Sunday August 24, 2014 - 02:47  pm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Video Libya: Inside Tripoli's battle-ravaged airport |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-africa-31030384/libya-inside-tripoli-s-battle-ravaged-airport |website=BBC news |publisher=BBC NEWS 28 Jan 2015 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe assault on the airport  and deteriorating security in Libya, prompted UN agencies to relocate its staff to neighboring countries. [[UNSMIL]] \"United Nations Support Mission in Libya\" to condemn the violence and the destruction of Civilian infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web |title=UNSMIL CONDEMNS AND CALLS FOR END TO TRIPOLI VIOLENCE, SUPPORT FOR EFFORTS TO RESTORE CALM |url=https://unsmil.unmissions.org/unsmil-condemns-and-calls-end-tripoli-violence-support-efforts-restore-calm |website=UNSMIL.org |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>, resulting in the UN to reiterate its support for a civilian government within Libya and strongly condemned attacks on civilians and infrastructure by adapting resolution 2174(2014), including later placing sanctions on [[Salah Badi]] in 2018 for his roles in the assault on Tripoli Airport.<ref>{{cite web |title=United Nations Security Council Report |url=https://www.un.org/securitycouncil/sanctions/1970/materials/summaries/individual/salah-badi |website=UN.org |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Assad |first1=AbdulKadder |title=UN Security Council sanctions Salah Badi |url=https://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/un-security-council-sanctions-salah-badi |website=The Libya Observer |publisher=The Libya Observer |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n'''More than 20 civilian aircraft''' were damaged or destroyed<ref>{{cite web |title=List of aircraft damaged during fighting at Tripoli Airport, Libya |url=https://news.aviation-safety.net/2014/08/31/list-of-aircraft-damaged-during-fighting-at-tripoli-airport-libya/ |website=Aviation Safety Network |publisher=ASN.NET  / Source : official sources |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>,<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya - On this day, corresponding to July 21, the Libyan aviation and air transport sector in 2014 received a severe blow by losing the majority of its air fleet owned by various airlines |url=https://almarsad.co/2018/07/21/\u0634\u0627\u0647\u062f-100-\u0635\u0648\u0631\u0629-\u062a\u062d\u0627\u0643\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0630\u0643\u0631\u0649-\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0639\u0629-\u0644\u0640-\u0627\u0644/ |website=Al Marsad |publisher=Al Marsad.co |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> of which 13 belonged to [[Afriqiyah Airways]] and 7 belonged to [[Lufthansa]]. The Airport's air traffic control tower, radar, four major fuel storage containers, main customs and reception building and terminals were destroyed.\n\nOn August 6, 2014,[[ Amnesty International]], [[UNSMIL]] and [[OHCHR]] reported a civilian death toll of 214 and 981<ref>{{cite web |title=OVERVIEW OF VIOLATIONS OF INTERNATIONAL HUMAN RIGHTS AND HUMANITARIAN LAW DURING THE ONGOING VIOLENCE IN LIBYA 4 September 2014 |url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Countries/LY/OverviewViolationsLibya_UNSMIL_OHCHR_Sept04_en.pdf |website=OHCHR.org |publisher=OHCHR - UNSMIL |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> injured due to indiscriminate shelling and violence inflicted by militias.<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya: Indiscriminate shelling of civilian areas in Tripoli and Benghazi amounts to war crimes |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2014/08/libya-indiscriminate-shelling-civilian-areas-tripoli-and-benghazi-amounts-war-crimes/ |website=Amnesty International |publisher=Amnesty International |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |title=Amnesty International Report 2014/15 - Libya |url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/54f07dce15.html |publisher=Amnesty International |via=UNHCR Refworld |date=25 February 2015 |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>[[OHCHR]] and [[UNSMIL]] reported that the ''UNSMIL believes that the casualty figures are an underestimate of the actual situation. Furthermore, it should be noted that Libyan health officials do not distinguish between fighters and civilians in issuing casualty figures, which makes it difficult to track the number of civilians killed in the conflict. This challenge is exacerbated because armed group members do not usually wear recognizable uniforms or carry distinctive insignia''<ref>{{cite web |title=OVERVIEW OF VIOLATIONS OF INTERNATIONAL HUMAN RIGHTS AND HUMANITARIAN LAW DURING THE ONGOING VIOLENCE IN LIBYA 4 September 2014 |url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Countries/LY/OverviewViolationsLibya_UNSMIL_OHCHR_Sept04_en.pdf |website=OHCHR.org |publisher=OHCHR & UNSMIL |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=Page 5 ( ii. Casualty figures )}}</ref>.\n\nFinancial losses suffered by the Airline Sector in Libya were roughly estimated to be around $3.5 billion for the destroyed aircraft alone, in addition to huge sums in damage incurred on the airport facility amounting to an estimated $US 70 million dollars for 90% of the facility's destruction.<ref name=lat-20140824>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-islamist-militias-libya-airport-20140824-story.html |title=Islamist militias seize main Libya airport as conflict deepens |author1=Muhamed Juma |author2=Amro Hassan |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=24 August 2014 |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>. [[Libyan Airlines]] a state owned company reported that its losses amounted to $US 200 million reported by its Manager, Ahmed Al Qadiri in a Statement to The New Arab news agency.<ref>{{cite web |title=3 Years for planes to resume flight \"3 \u0633\u0646\u0648\u0627\u062a \u0644\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0639\u0627\u062f\u0629 \u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u064a \u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627\" |url=Https://www.alaraby.co.uk/economy/2014/11/22/3-\u0633\u0646\u0648\u0627\u062a-\u0644\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0639\u0627\u062f\u0629-\u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646-\u0641\u064a-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627 |website=Al Arabi Al Jadeed www.alaraby.co.uk |publisher=Al Arabi Al Jadeed ( The New Arab) November 22, 2014 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn July 13th, 2014, The Zintani forces within the airport withdrew on Orders from the parliament thus ending the battle at the airport.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zintan \u201cordered\u201d to withdraw from Tripoli by HoR |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2014/08/24/zintan-ordered-to-withdraw-from-tripoli-by-hor/ |website=Libya Herald |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn September 8th 2014, Human rights watch released a statement condemning violence by both main Militia parties and stated that actions taken by Militias may amount to war crimes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya: Spiraling Militia Attacks May Be War Crimes |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/09/08/libya-spiraling-militia-attacks-may-be-war-crimes |website=Human Rights watch |publisher=Human Rights watch September 8, 2014 10:49AM EDT |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nBy April 2019, the non-functional Tripoli international Airport was captured<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ucar |first1=Mehmet |title=Libya: Pro-Haftar forces seize Tripoli airport |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/libya-pro-haftar-forces-seize-tripoli-airport/1443725 |website=Anadolu Agency |publisher=Anadolu Agency |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> by the [[Libyan National Army]] and is used as a strategic staging ground for the [[Libyan National Army|LNA]] operation against [[Libya Dawn]] Islamist in Tripoli.<ref>{{cite web |title=LNA controls Tripoli international Airport - Live UA map war tracking |url=https://libya.liveuamap.com/en/2019/5-april-lna-controls-tripoli-international-airport |website=liveuamap |publisher=Live UA maps |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2014|Tripoli Airport]]\n[[Category:History of Tripoli]]\n[[Category:21st century in Tripoli]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the Second Libyan Civil War in 2014|Tripoli Airport]]\n[[Category:July 2014 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:August 2014 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving airports]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Tripoli Airport\n|partof=the [[2014 Libyan conflict]]\n| image= Tripoli Airport.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=Tripoli International Airport\n|date=13 July \u2013 23 August 2014<br>({{Age in months, weeks and days|month1=07|day1=13|year1=2014|month2=08|day2=23|year2=2014}})\n|place=[[Tripoli International Airport]], [[Libya]]\n|territory=\n|result=Libya Dawn victory\n*[[Zintan]]i forces and their allies withdraw on orders of [[House of Representatives (Libya)|House of Representatives]]\n*Islamist armed groups take control of the airport\n*Airport now unused\n|combatants_header=Belligerents<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/security/2014/08/libya-tripoli-control-hifter-tribal-forces.html | title=Dawn of Libya forces impose control on Tripoli | publisher=Al-Monitor | date=August 25, 2014 | accessdate=August 27, 2014 | author=Daleh, Mustafa}}</ref>\n|combatant1={{Flagicon|Libya}} [[Zintan Brigade|Zintani brigades]]\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}} Al-Qaqa battalion\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}} Al Sawa'iq battalion\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}} Warshefana battalions\n*Zintani Airport Security\n----\n'''Supported by:'''\n*{{flag|Egypt}}<ref name=\"egyptuae\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/26/world/africa/egypt-and-united-arab-emirates-said-to-have-secretly-carried-out-libya-airstrikes.html | title=Egypt and United Arab Emirates Said to Have Secretly Carried Out Libya Airstrikes | publisher=The New York Times | date=August 25, 2014 | accessdate=August 25, 2014 | author=[[David D. Kirkpatrick|D. Kirkpatrick, David]] |author2=Schmitt, Eric}}</ref><ref>http://www.libyaherald.com/2014/08/28/egypt-prepared-to-take-lead-in-ensuring-stability-in-libya/</ref>\n*{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}<ref name=\"egyptuae\"/>\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Libyan National Army]]\n\n|combatant2={{Flagicon|Libya}} Libya Dawn coalition\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Libya Revolutionaries Operations Room]]\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Libya Shield Force|Central Shield]] Misrata brigades\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Al Somoud Battalion]] \n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Ghnewa Al Kikli Battalion]]\n*{{Flagicon|Libya}}[[Al Qabra Battalion]]\n*[[File:Flag of Jihad.svg|25px]][[Ansar al-Sharia (Libya)]]\n\n----\n'''Supported by:'''\n*{{flag|Qatar}}<ref name=\"egyptuae\"/>\n*{{flag|Turkey}}\n\n|commander1=\n|commander2={{Flagicon|Libya}} [[Nouri Abusahmain]]<br>([[List of heads of state of Libya|President of the GNC]], disputed)<br>\n{{Flagicon|Libya}} [[Sadiq Al-Ghariani]]<br>([[Grand Mufti]])<br>\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Libya.svg}} [[Mohammed Hadia]]<br>(Operation Libya Dawn Commander)<br>\n{{Flagicon image|<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: Flag of the Joint Operations Room of Libya\u2019s Revolutionaries.svg -->}}  [[Shaaban Hadia]]<br>(LROR Commander)\n|strength1=\n|strength2=\n|casualties3=\n|notes=\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox 2014 Libyan Civil War}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Tripoli Airport''' was a battle of the [[Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|Libyan Civil War]]. It began on 13 July 2014 as part of the \"[[Libya Dawn]]\" Coalition operation and ended in August 2014. The battle was fought between a [[Islamist]] [[New General National Congress]] coalition and the [[Zintan Brigade|Zintani brigades]].\n\n==Background==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Tripoli (June 15 2014).png|thumb|left|Situation in Tripoli mid June 2014; airport is further south]]\nThe Zintani Brigades had provided security for Tripoli International Airport since the 2011 War which overthrew [[Gadhafi]].\n\nAfter the defeat of Islamist politicians in the [[2014 Libyan parliamentary election]], the [[Libya Revolutionaries Operations Room]] and [[Misrata Brigades]] were faced with a largely anti-Islamist [[House of Representatives (Libya)|parliament]]. Their most powerful political ally, [[Nouri Abusahmain]], was faced with an imminent loss of power, and they were likely to lose funding from the [[General National Congress]]. The anti-Islamist politicians who won the 2014 elections had previously tried to disband the Libya Revolutionaries Operations Room due to its attempted coup in 2013, and were able to do so after the election results.\n\n==Combatants==\nThe New General National Congress coalition, dubbed operation [[Libya Dawn]] was composed of the [[Libya Revolutionaries Operations Room]] included the following groups:\n*[[Misrata battalion|Misrata's]] Al Somood batallion led by Salah Badi<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya airport takeover widens political split |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/08/libya-airport-takeover-tripoli-political-split-20148249154577648.html |website=Aljazeera English |publisher=Aljazeera English News - 24 Aug 2014 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Military leader that burned Tripoli airport of the capital of Libya to cleanse it from \"Corruption\". |url=https://elqalamcenter.com/2018/08/29/\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0626\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0633\u0643\u0631\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a-\u0623\u062d\u0631\u0642-\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633-\u064a/ |website=Al-Qalam Center for Research and Studies |publisher=Al-Qalam Center for Research and Studies |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tripoli is Again Without an Airport Since Salah Badi\u2019s 2014 Attack |url=https://almarsad.co/en/2019/09/02/tripoli-is-again-without-an-airport-since-salah-badis-2014-attack/ |website=Almarsad.co |publisher=Almarsad news |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Ghnewa battalion]] led by Abdul Ghani Al-Kikli<ref>{{cite web |last1=Arfaoui |first1=Jamel |title=Who is Abdulghani Al Kikli? |url=https://tunisie-telegraph.com/2014/07/29/\u062a\u0648\u0631\u0637-\u0641\u064a-\u062d\u0631\u064a\u0642-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633-\u0648\u062c\u0627\u0621-\u0644\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u062c-\u0641\u064a-\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0633-4434 |website=Tunisie Telegraph (Tunisian Telegraph) |publisher=Tunisie Telegraph 29-07-2014 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=5 points of information you didnt know about Ghnewa Al Kikli |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/5-\u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645\u0627\u062a-\u0642\u062f-\u0644\u0627-\u062a\u0639\u0631\u0641\u0647\u0627-\u0639\u0646-\u063a\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0643\u0644\u064a/ |website=Afrigatenews.net |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=All you need to know about \"Operation Dawn of Libya\" |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0643\u0644-\u0645\u0627-\u062a\u0631\u064a\u062f-\u0623\u0646-\u062a\u0639\u0631\u0641\u0647-\u0639\u0646-\u0639\u0645\u0644\u064a\u0629-\u0641\u062c\u0631-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627/ |website=AfrigateNews.net - Africa news portal |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>, \n*Al-Qabra battalion led by Suleiman Al Shatwan.<ref>{{cite web |title=All you need to know about \"Operation Dawn of Libya\" |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0643\u0644-\u0645\u0627-\u062a\u0631\u064a\u062f-\u0623\u0646-\u062a\u0639\u0631\u0641\u0647-\u0639\u0646-\u0639\u0645\u0644\u064a\u0629-\u0641\u062c\u0631-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627/ |website=Afrigate News |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Misrata leader in the Misrata battalion killed in Tripoli airport clashes |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0645\u0642\u062a\u0644-\u0642\u064a\u0627\u062f\u064a-\u0641\u064a-\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0626\u0628-\u0645\u0635\u0631\u0627\u062a\u0629-\u0641\u064a-\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0643\u0627\u062a-\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633/ |website=AfrigateNews.net |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Supported by Qatari and Turkish military training, Intelligence and arms support<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkey, Qatar accused of delivering weapons to Libyan militants |url=https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/2/7972/Turkey-Qatar-accused-of-delivering-weapons-to-Libyan-militants |website=Egypt Today |publisher=Egypt Today, Sat, Jun. 17, 2017 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=United nations Security council report S/2014/106 |journal=UN Security Council report S/2014/106 |date=19 February 2014 |issue=S/2014/106 |pages=20/97  (67.) |url=https://www.securitycouncilreport.org/atf/cf/%7B65BFCF9B-6D27-4E9C-8CD3-CF6E4FF96FF9%7D/s_2014_106.pdf |accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref=67. Greece confirmed that the ship arrived in Volos on 24 January 2013 from Derince, Turkey.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Death Ships: The Chronology of Turkish Weapons Ships to Libya |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0633\u0641\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u062a-\u0643\u0631\u0646\u0648\u0644\u0648\u062c\u064a\u0627-\u0633\u0641\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u0644\u062d\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0643\u064a\u0629-\u0625\u0644\u0649-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627/ |website=AfrigateNews.net |publisher=Afrigate News |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wehrey |first1=Frederic |title=Is Libya a proxy war? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2014/10/24/is-libya-a-proxy-war/ |website=Washington Post |publisher=Washington Post October 24, 2014 at 5:00 PM EDT |accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref=\", with their respective special forces supporting disparate revolutionary factions with intelligence, training and arms. \"}}</ref>. \n\nThe Zintani-led brigades consisted of the following groups: \n*Al-Qaqa battallion<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya, Militias burn down Tripoli airport after capturing it. |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/north-africa/libya/2014/08/24/\u0627\u0644\u0635\u0648\u0631-\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644\u0649-\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0642-\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633-\u0639\u0644\u0649-\u064a\u062f-\u0645\u064a\u0644\u064a\u0634\u064a\u0627\u062a-\u0645\u062a\u0637\u0631\u0641\u0629 |website=Al Arabiya |publisher=Al Arabiya |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> led by Maj.Gen. Othman Al Mulaitaqa<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya Qaqaa Batalion, Defending Tripoli from Hostiles |url=https://aawsat.com/home/article/41516 |website=Al Sharq Alwast |publisher=AlSharq-Alwast, aawsat.com/ |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Libyan militias withdraw from the capital, Tripoli |url=https://www.bbc.com/arabic/middleeast/2013/11/131121_libya_militias_withdraw_from_tripoli |website=BBC news Arabic |publisher=BBC NEWS Arabic |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Al-Sawa'iq battalion<ref>{{cite book |title=Libya: Security Situation report |date=19 December 2014 |publisher=US Department of Justice website \"Justic.gov\" |pages=14 / 76 |ref=3.2.4 The Zintan battalion}}</ref> led by Imad Mustafa Traboulsi<ref>{{cite web |title=Discover 6 information about Emad Trabelsi |url=Https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0643\u062a\u0634\u0641-6-\u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645\u0627\u062a-\u0639\u0646-\u0639\u0645\u0627\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633\u064a/ |website=AfrigateNews.Net |publisher=Afrigatenews.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n*Members of [[:ar:\u0648\u0631\u0634\u0641\u0627\u0646\u0629|Warshefana]] battalions. \n*Received materiel and Air support from the [[Libyan National Army]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The Libyan National Army claims responsibility for bombing armed militants in Tripoli |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/north-africa/libya/2014/08/18/\u0637\u0627\u0626\u0631\u0627\u062a-\u062d\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629-\u0645\u062c\u0647\u0648\u0644\u0629-\u0641\u064a-\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0621-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0635\u0645\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0629 |website=Al Arabiya news |publisher=Al Arabiya News |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Conflicting accounts of Libyan Tripoli raids |url=ttps://www.aljazeera.net/news/arabic/2014/8/19/\u062a\u0636\u0627\u0631\u0628-\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0648\u0627\u064a\u0627\u062a-\u0628\u0634\u0623\u0646-\u063a\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0629 |website=Aljazeera Arabic |publisher=Aljazeera Arabic |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Unidentified aircraft bomb the \"Dawn of Libya\" forces in Tripoli |url=https://www.aljazeera.net/news/arabic/2014/8/18/\u0637\u0627\u0626\u0631\u0627\u062a-\u0645\u062c\u0647\u0648\u0644\u0629-\u062a\u0642\u0635\u0641-\u0642\u0648\u0627\u062a-\u0641\u062c\u0631-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627-\u0648\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0643\u0627\u062a-\u0628\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633 |website=Aljazeera News Arabic |publisher=Aljazeera Arabic |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n\nOn 13 July the Libya Dawn coalition launched their operation to seize the airport. Many aircraft were destroyed on the ground. The operation received public support from [[Grand Mufti]] [[Sadiq Al-Ghariani]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya\u2019s highest spiritual leader banned from UK over support of Islamists |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/30/libya-spiritual-leader-banned-uk-islamists |website=The Guardian |publisher=The guardian |accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref=\"Speaking from the UK via the Libyan television station Tanasuh, the radical cleric celebrated the violent capture of Tripoli by Islamist militia force Libya Dawn, and ordered a widening of the rebellion.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Radical Cleric Al-Ghariani: Rebel Leaders Are Corrupt And LPA Is \u201cA Lost Deal\u201d! |url=https://www.addresslibya.com/en/archives/30621 |website=The Libyan Adress |publisher=The Libyan Adress 19 July\u060c 2018 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mustafa |first1=Ajnadin |title=Grand Mufti again backs Libya Dawn operation, calls Zintanis and allies \u201ctraitors\u201d |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2014/08/21/grand-mufti-again-backs-libya-dawn-operation-calls-zintanis-and-allies-traitors/ |website=Libya Herald |publisher=Libya Herald |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\nOn 23 August 2014, Zintani forces withdrew from the airport. They claimed that they withdrew because they had been instructed to do so by the parliament. This was later confirmed by parliamentary sources.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn the immediate aftermath of the battle, large fires and plumes of smoke arose from 4 large kerosene fuel containers that were struck by rocket attacks,<ref>{{cite web |title=\" A fourth oil depot ignited near the Tripoli airport\" Arabic: \"\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0644 \u0645\u0633\u062a\u0648\u062f\u0639 \u0646\u0641\u0637 \u0631\u0627\u0628\u0639 \u0642\u0631\u0628 \u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633\" |url=https://www.afrigatenews.net/article/\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0644-\u0645\u0633\u062a\u0648\u062f\u0639-\u0646\u0641\u0637-\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0639-\u0642\u0631\u0628-\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631-\u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633 |website=AfrigateNews.net |publisher=Afrigate News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fuel Tank Blaze Near Tripoli Airport 'Out of Control' |url=https://www.voanews.com/africa/fuel-tank-blaze-near-tripoli-airport-out-control |website=VOA News |publisher=Voice of America |accessdate=26 March 2020 |ref=July 28, 2014 02:45 AM}}</ref> polluting the surrounding grounds and the air quality.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amara |first1=Hani |title=Fuel tanks hit in clashes near Libyan airport |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security/fuel-tanks-hit-in-clashes-near-libyan-airport-idUSKBN0FS16U20140723 |website=Reuters News |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Roads infrastructure on the exterior of the airport facility was damaged as well as inside the airport with mortar explosions and shrapnel. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sim |first1=David |title=Libya: Burnt-out Planes Litter Runway as Battle for Tripoli Airport Continues [PHOTOS] |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/libya-burnt-out-planes-litter-runway-battle-tripoli-airport-continues-photos-1457750 |website=International Business Times |publisher=David Sim, International Business Times, July 22, 2014 13:22 BST |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Turkia |first1=Hamza |title=30 dead in Libya int'l airport attack (4) |url=http://en.people.cn/n/2014/0717/c90777-8756909-4.html |website=Peoples Daily Online |publisher=Peoples Daily, Xinhua/Hamza Turkia |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Residential areas near to the airport were also damaged in the fighting, as some residences were used in the fighting as firing positions by all involved parties. \nResidential areas surrounding the airport were also damaged during the battle, mostly from light weapons [[7.62x32]], heavy weapons damage from [[zsu-23-2]] projectiles, [[RPG-7]] and on rare occasions larger damage from [[T-72]] rounds. There have been reports of violations against civilians<ref>{{cite web |title=OVERVIEW OF VIOLATIONS OF INTERNATIONAL HUMAN RIGHTS AND HUMANITARIAN LAW DURING THE ONGOING VIOLENCE IN LIBYA 4 September 2014 |url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Countries/LY/OverviewViolationsLibya_UNSMIL_OHCHR_Sept04_en.pdf |website=Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights OHCHR & UNSMIL |publisher=OHCHR - UN 4 September 2014 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>, and [[BM-21 Grad|GRAD]] rocket systems being used on civilian residential areas, with civilians caught in the crossfire despite many of them being displaced.<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya: Spiraling Militia Attacks May Be War Crimes |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/09/08/libya-spiraling-militia-attacks-may-be-war-crimes |website=Human Rights watch |publisher=Human Rights watch |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tripoli airport 2.jpg|thumb|Fires burning at the customs building of Tripoli international Airport in 2014]]\nThe airport main reception and customs building succumbed to catastrophic fire damage after an intense assault was launched by Islamist Libya Dawn and Al Somood militias to capture the facility during the final days of the battle which resulted in the defending Zintani forces withdrawing from the airport.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leaded Video shows Salah Badi within Tripoli Airport on the day it was captured by Libya Dawn Forces. |url=https://almarsad.co/2016/11/07/\u0641\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0648-\u0645\u0633\u0631\u0628-\u064a\u0638\u0647\u0631-\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d-\u0628\u0627\u062f\u064a-\u062f\u0627\u062e\u0644-\u0645\u0628\u0646\u0649-\u0645\u0637\u0627/ |website=Almarsad.co |publisher=AlMarsad.co |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>.\nThe entirety of the interior of the reception building that housed offices and processing areas, containing flammable materials completely burned off, rendering the mail building unusable.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Masdar News |first1=Masdar news |title=\"First pictures of the burning of the Airport caused by Extremists\" \" \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644\u0649 \u0644\u062d\u0631\u0642 \u0645\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0637\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u064a\u062f \u0645\u064a\u0644\u064a\u0634\u064a\u0627\u062a \u0645\u062a\u0637\u0631\u0641\u0629\" |url=https://www.almasdar.com/2352 |website=Al-Masdar |publisher=AL Masdar News |accessdate=26 March 2020 |ref=Sunday August 24, 2014 - 02:47  pm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Video Libya: Inside Tripoli's battle-ravaged airport |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-africa-31030384/libya-inside-tripoli-s-battle-ravaged-airport |website=BBC news |publisher=BBC NEWS 28 Jan 2015 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe assault on the airport  and deteriorating security in Libya, prompted UN agencies to relocate its staff to neighboring countries. [[UNSMIL]] \"United Nations Support Mission in Libya\" to condemn the violence and the destruction of Civilian infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web |title=UNSMIL CONDEMNS AND CALLS FOR END TO TRIPOLI VIOLENCE, SUPPORT FOR EFFORTS TO RESTORE CALM |url=https://unsmil.unmissions.org/unsmil-condemns-and-calls-end-tripoli-violence-support-efforts-restore-calm |website=UNSMIL.org |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>, resulting in the UN to reiterate its support for a civilian government within Libya and strongly condemned attacks on civilians and infrastructure by adapting resolution 2174(2014), including later placing sanctions on [[Salah Badi]] in 2018 for his roles in the assault on Tripoli Airport.<ref>{{cite web |title=United Nations Security Council Report |url=https://www.un.org/securitycouncil/sanctions/1970/materials/summaries/individual/salah-badi |website=UN.org |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Assad |first1=AbdulKadder |title=UN Security Council sanctions Salah Badi |url=https://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/un-security-council-sanctions-salah-badi |website=The Libya Observer |publisher=The Libya Observer |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n'''More than 20 civilian aircraft''' were damaged or destroyed<ref>{{cite web |title=List of aircraft damaged during fighting at Tripoli Airport, Libya |url=https://news.aviation-safety.net/2014/08/31/list-of-aircraft-damaged-during-fighting-at-tripoli-airport-libya/ |website=Aviation Safety Network |publisher=ASN.NET  / Source : official sources |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>,<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya - On this day, corresponding to July 21, the Libyan aviation and air transport sector in 2014 received a severe blow by losing the majority of its air fleet owned by various airlines |url=https://almarsad.co/2018/07/21/\u0634\u0627\u0647\u062f-100-\u0635\u0648\u0631\u0629-\u062a\u062d\u0627\u0643\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0630\u0643\u0631\u0649-\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0639\u0629-\u0644\u0640-\u0627\u0644/ |website=Al Marsad |publisher=Al Marsad.co |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> of which 13 belonged to [[Afriqiyah Airways]] and 7 belonged to [[Lufthansa]]. The Airport's air traffic control tower, radar, four major fuel storage containers, main customs and reception building and terminals were destroyed.\n\nOn August 6, 2014,[[ Amnesty International]], [[UNSMIL]] and [[OHCHR]] reported a civilian death toll of 214 and 981<ref>{{cite web |title=OVERVIEW OF VIOLATIONS OF INTERNATIONAL HUMAN RIGHTS AND HUMANITARIAN LAW DURING THE ONGOING VIOLENCE IN LIBYA 4 September 2014 |url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Countries/LY/OverviewViolationsLibya_UNSMIL_OHCHR_Sept04_en.pdf |website=OHCHR.org |publisher=OHCHR - UNSMIL |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> injured due to indiscriminate shelling and violence inflicted by militias.<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya: Indiscriminate shelling of civilian areas in Tripoli and Benghazi amounts to war crimes |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2014/08/libya-indiscriminate-shelling-civilian-areas-tripoli-and-benghazi-amounts-war-crimes/ |website=Amnesty International |publisher=Amnesty International |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |title=Amnesty International Report 2014/15 - Libya |url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/54f07dce15.html |publisher=Amnesty International |via=UNHCR Refworld |date=25 February 2015 |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>[[OHCHR]] and [[UNSMIL]] reported that the ''UNSMIL believes that the casualty figures are an underestimate of the actual situation. Furthermore, it should be noted that Libyan health officials do not distinguish between fighters and civilians in issuing casualty figures, which makes it difficult to track the number of civilians killed in the conflict. This challenge is exacerbated because armed group members do not usually wear recognizable uniforms or carry distinctive insignia''<ref>{{cite web |title=OVERVIEW OF VIOLATIONS OF INTERNATIONAL HUMAN RIGHTS AND HUMANITARIAN LAW DURING THE ONGOING VIOLENCE IN LIBYA 4 September 2014 |url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Countries/LY/OverviewViolationsLibya_UNSMIL_OHCHR_Sept04_en.pdf |website=OHCHR.org |publisher=OHCHR & UNSMIL |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=Page 5 ( ii. Casualty figures )}}</ref>.\n\nFinancial losses suffered by the Airline Sector in Libya were roughly estimated to be around $3.5 billion for the destroyed aircraft alone, in addition to huge sums in damage incurred on the airport facility amounting to an estimated $US 70 million dollars for 90% of the facility's destruction.<ref name=lat-20140824>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-islamist-militias-libya-airport-20140824-story.html |title=Islamist militias seize main Libya airport as conflict deepens |author1=Muhamed Juma |author2=Amro Hassan |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=24 August 2014 |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>. [[Libyan Airlines]] a state owned company reported that its losses amounted to $US 200 million reported by its Manager, Ahmed Al Qadiri in a Statement to The New Arab news agency.<ref>{{cite web |title=3 Years for planes to resume flight \"3 \u0633\u0646\u0648\u0627\u062a \u0644\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0639\u0627\u062f\u0629 \u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u064a \u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627\" |url=Https://www.alaraby.co.uk/economy/2014/11/22/3-\u0633\u0646\u0648\u0627\u062a-\u0644\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0639\u0627\u062f\u0629-\u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646-\u0641\u064a-\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a\u0627 |website=Al Arabi Al Jadeed www.alaraby.co.uk |publisher=Al Arabi Al Jadeed ( The New Arab) November 22, 2014 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn July 13th, 2014, The Zintani forces within the airport withdrew on Orders from the parliament thus ending the battle at the airport.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zintan \u201cordered\u201d to withdraw from Tripoli by HoR |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2014/08/24/zintan-ordered-to-withdraw-from-tripoli-by-hor/ |website=Libya Herald |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn September 8th 2014, Human rights watch released a statement condemning violence by both main Militia parties and stated that actions taken by Militias may amount to war crimes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya: Spiraling Militia Attacks May Be War Crimes |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/09/08/libya-spiraling-militia-attacks-may-be-war-crimes |website=Human Rights watch |publisher=Human Rights watch September 8, 2014 10:49AM EDT |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nBy April 2019, the non-functional Tripoli international Airport was captured<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ucar |first1=Mehmet |title=Libya: Pro-Haftar forces seize Tripoli airport |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/libya-pro-haftar-forces-seize-tripoli-airport/1443725 |website=Anadolu Agency |publisher=Anadolu Agency |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> by the [[Libyan National Army]] and is used as a strategic staging ground for the [[Libyan National Army|LNA]] operation against [[Libya Dawn]] Islamist in Tripoli.<ref>{{cite web |title=LNA controls Tripoli international Airport - Live UA map war tracking |url=https://libya.liveuamap.com/en/2019/5-april-lna-controls-tripoli-international-airport |website=liveuamap |publisher=Live UA maps |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2014|Tripoli Airport]]\n[[Category:History of Tripoli]]\n[[Category:21st century in Tripoli]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the Second Libyan Civil War in 2014|Tripoli Airport]]\n[[Category:July 2014 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:August 2014 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving airports]]\n", "name_user": "Biomax20", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAftermath", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Tripoli_Airport"}
{"title_page": "West Kowloon", "text_new": "{{About|the geographical area of Hong Kong|the geographical constituencies|Kowloon West (constituency)}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Union Square Overview 201008.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The [[Union Square (Hong Kong)|Union Square]] development.]]\n[[File:West Kowloon Olympic Station Buildings 20110510.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Olympic Station have several high-rise residential]]\n[[File:Hong Kong West Kowloon Station view 201810.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[West Kowloon Terminus]] The Terminus of [[Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link|Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong HSR]]]]\n[[File:The Long Beach GF Open Space 2012.jpg|thumb|300px|The Long Beach Public open spaces]]\n\n'''West Kowloon''' ({{zh|t=\u897f\u4e5d\u9f8d}}) is a part of [[Kowloon]], Hong Kong situated within the [[Yau Tsim Mong District]]. It is bounded by Canton Road to the east, [[Victoria Harbour]] to the west and the south, and [[Jordan Road, Hong Kong|Jordan Road]] to the north. Further to the north, the area extends to [[Tai Kok Tsui]] to the west of the West Kowloon Expressway. [[Nam Cheong Station|Nam Cheong]], [[Olympic (MTR)|Olympic]], [[Austin station (MTR)|Austin]] and [[Kowloon (MTR)|Kowloon]] stations are within the area.\n\nIt is principally a stretch of [[Land reclamation in Hong Kong|reclaimed land]], which was subsequently developed in the late 20th century. It has been zoned for mixed commercial, residential and leisure development, and was almost doubled in size with a large reclamation scheme as part of the [[Airport Core Programme]].\n\n== Structures ==\n\n=== Existing ===\n[[File:Western Harbour Tunnel.JPG|thumb|The Western Harbour tunnel connects West Kowloon to HK island]]\n* [[West Kowloon Waterfront Promenade]]\n* [[West Kowloon Corridor]] - a bypass connecting [[Lai Chi Kok Road]] with the [[Gascoigne Road Flyover]] in Yau Ma Tei\n* [[Western Harbour Crossing]] - Hong Kong's third harbour crossing, the Kowloon portal of which is located within West Kowloon\n* [[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon Station]], [[Austin Station (MTR)|Austin Station]], [[Olympic station]] and [[Nam Cheong Station]] of [[MTR]]\n* [[Hong Kong West Kowloon railway station]] - Hong Kong's high speed rail terminal connecting mainland China.\n* [[International Commerce Centre]] - the current tallest building in Hong Kong\n\n=== Constructing ===\n* [[West Kowloon Cultural District]] - proposal for a leisure and cultural district\n\n=== Under planning ===\n* [[Central Kowloon Route]] Yau Ma Tei interchange\n\n== Projects ==\n\n=== Realised or in progress ===\nCommercial projects include [[International Commerce Centre]], a 484 m (1,588&nbsp;ft.) skyscraper which is part of the [[Union Square, Hong Kong|Union Square project]].\n\nResidential projects which have been realised in the sector include The Waterfront (''2000''), [[Sorrento, Hong Kong|Sorrento]] (''2003''), the tallest residential building in Hong Kong, [[The Harbourside]] (''2003''), and [[The Arch (Hong Kong)|The Arch]] (''2005''), The Cullinan (''2008''). The above all sit atop [[Kowloon (MTR)|Kowloon MTR station]], a station on the [[Tung Chung Line (MTR)|Tung Chung Line]] and [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express Line]]. The shopping-mall [[Elements, Hong Kong|Elements]] started operating on 1 October 2007.\n\n=== Plots auctioned ===\nIn August 2005, two neighbouring sites near Central Park and Park Avenue were triggered for auction, and were subsequently acquired by a joint venture of Sino Land, Chinese Estates Holdings and Nan Fung Development.<ref>Raymond Wang and Danny Chung, [http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=48&art_id=43596&sid=13386356&con_type=1&d_str=20070504&sear_year=2007 West Kowloon braces for battle], ''[[The Standard (Hong Kong)|The Standard]]'', 4 May 2007</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, a site bounded by Hoi Wang Road, Yan Cheung Road and Yau Cheung Road was won by a consortium comprising Sino Land, Chinese Estates Holdings, K Wah International and Nan Fung Development, for a bid of HK$4&nbsp;billion.<ref>Raymond Wang and Danny Chung, [http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=2&art_id=44036&sid=13509838&con_type=3&d_str=20070509&sear_year=2007 Low-end $4b win], ''[[The Standard (Hong Kong)|The Standard]]'', 9 May 2007</ref> Following the successful auction of the site, some legislators called for a law to stop developers from constructing tall buildings which maximise good views at the expense of air flow in densely populated areas, but the bid failed.<ref>Olga Wong, \"Call for law against 'wall effect' fails\", ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 10 May 2007</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Kowloon West|West Kowloon}}\n{{coords|22.3036|114.1600|format=dms|display=t}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:West Kowloon| ]]\n[[Category:Restricted areas of Hong Kong red public minibus]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the geographical area of Hong Kong|the geographical constituencies|Kowloon West (constituency)}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n[[File:Union Square Overview 201008.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The [[Union Square (Hong Kong)|Union Square]] development.]]\n[[File:West Kowloon Olympic Station Buildings 20110510.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Olympic Station have several high-rise residential]]\n[[File:Hong Kong West Kowloon Station view 201810.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[West Kowloon Terminus]] The Terminus of [[Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link|Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong HSR]]]]\n[[File:The Long Beach GF Open Space 2012.jpg|thumb|300px|The Long Beach Public open spaces]]\n\n'''West Kowloon''' ({{zh|t=\u897f\u4e5d\u9f8d}}) is a part of [[Kowloon]], Hong Kong situated within the [[Yau Tsim Mong District]]. It is bounded by Canton Road to the east, [[Victoria Harbour]] to the west and the south, and [[Jordan Road, Hong Kong|Jordan Road]] to the north. Further to the north, the area extends to [[Tai Kok Tsui]] to the west of the West Kowloon Expressway. [[Nam Cheong Station|Nam Cheong]], [[Olympic (MTR)|Olympic]], [[Austin station (MTR)|Austin]] and [[Kowloon (MTR)|Kowloon]] stations are within the area.\n\nIt is principally a stretch of [[Land reclamation in Hong Kong|reclaimed land]], which was subsequently developed in the late 20th century. It has been zoned for mixed commercial, residential and leisure development, and was almost doubled in size with a large reclamation scheme as part of the [[Airport Core Programme]].\n\n== Structures ==\n\n=== Existing ===\n[[File:Western Harbour Tunnel.JPG|thumb| The Western Harbour tunnel connects West Kowloon to HK island]]\n* [[West Kowloon Waterfront Promenade]]\n* [[West Kowloon Corridor]] - a bypass connecting [[Lai Chi Kok Road]] with the [[Gascoigne Road Flyover]] in Yau Ma Tei\n* [[Western Harbour Crossing]] - Hong Kong's third harbour crossing, the Kowloon portal of which is located within West Kowloon\n* [[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon Station]], [[Austin Station (MTR)|Austin Station]], [[Olympic station]] and [[Nam Cheong Station]] of [[MTR]]\n* [[Hong Kong West Kowloon railway station]] - Hong Kong's high speed rail terminal connecting mainland China.\n* [[International Commerce Centre]] - the current tallest building in Hong Kong\n\n=== Constructing ===\n* [[West Kowloon Cultural District]] - proposal for a leisure and cultural district\n\n=== Under planning ===\n* [[Central Kowloon Route]] Yau Ma Tei interchange\n\n== Projects ==\n\n=== Realised or in progress ===\nCommercial projects include [[International Commerce Centre]], a 484 m (1,588&nbsp;ft.) skyscraper which is part of the [[Union Square, Hong Kong|Union Square project]].\n\nResidential projects which have been realised in the sector include The Waterfront (''2000''), [[Sorrento, Hong Kong|Sorrento]] (''2003''), the tallest residential building in Hong Kong, [[The Harbourside]] (''2003''), and [[The Arch (Hong Kong)|The Arch]] (''2005''), The Cullinan (''2008''). The above all sit atop [[Kowloon (MTR)|Kowloon MTR station]], a station on the [[Tung Chung Line (MTR)|Tung Chung Line]] and [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express Line]]. The shopping-mall [[Elements, Hong Kong|Elements]] started operating on 1 October 2007.\n\n=== Plots auctioned ===\nIn August 2005, two neighbouring sites near Central Park and Park Avenue were triggered for auction, and were subsequently acquired by a joint venture of Sino Land, Chinese Estates Holdings and Nan Fung Development.<ref>Raymond Wang and Danny Chung, [http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=48&art_id=43596&sid=13386356&con_type=1&d_str=20070504&sear_year=2007 West Kowloon braces for battle], ''[[The Standard (Hong Kong)|The Standard]]'', 4 May 2007</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, a site bounded by Hoi Wang Road, Yan Cheung Road and Yau Cheung Road was won by a consortium comprising Sino Land, Chinese Estates Holdings, K Wah International and Nan Fung Development, for a bid of HK$4&nbsp;billion.<ref>Raymond Wang and Danny Chung, [http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=2&art_id=44036&sid=13509838&con_type=3&d_str=20070509&sear_year=2007 Low-end $4b win], ''[[The Standard (Hong Kong)|The Standard]]'', 9 May 2007</ref> Following the successful auction of the site, some legislators called for a law to stop developers from constructing tall buildings which maximise good views at the expense of air flow in densely populated areas, but the bid failed.<ref>Olga Wong, \"Call for law against 'wall effect' fails\", ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 10 May 2007</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Kowloon West|West Kowloon}}\n{{coords|22.3036|114.1600|format=dms|display=t}}\n\n[[Category:West Kowloon| ]]\n[[Category:Restricted areas of Hong Kong red public minibus]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Kowloon"}
{"title_page": "American Hot Wax", "text_new": "{{short description|1978 film by Floyd Mutrux}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name        = American Hot Wax\n| image       = American Hot Wax.jpg\n| caption     = Theatrical release poster\n| director    = [[Floyd Mutrux]]\n| producer    = [[Art Linson]]\n| screenplay  = [[John Kaye (screenwriter)|John Kaye]]\n| story       = John Kaye<br/>Art Linson\n| starring    = [[Tim McIntire]]<br/>[[Fran Drescher]]<br/>[[Jay Leno]]<br/>[[Laraine Newman]]<br/>[[Moosie Drier]]<br/>[[Jeff Altman]]<br/>John Lehne<br/>[[Richard Perry]]<br/>[[Chuck Berry]]<br/>[[Jerry Lee Lewis]]<br/>[[Screamin' Jay Hawkins]]<br/>[[Frankie Ford]]<br/>Charles Greene\n| editing     = Ronald J. Fagan<br />Melvin Shapiro<br />[[Danford B. Greene]] (sup)\n| cinematography = [[William A. Fraker]]\n| music       = [[Kenny Vance]] \n| studio      = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| distributor = Paramount Pictures\n| runtime     = 91 minutes\n| released    = {{Film date|1978|03|17}}\n| country     = United States\n| language    = English\n| budget      = \n| gross       = $11,000,000<ref name=\"numbers\">[http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/American-Hot-Wax#tab=summary Box Office Information for ''American Hot Wax''.] [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]. Retrieved July 18, 2014.</ref>\n}}\n'''''American Hot Wax''''' is a 1978 [[biographical film]] directed by [[Floyd Mutrux]] with a screenplay [[John Kaye (screenwriter)|John Kaye]] from a story by [[Art Linson]]. The film tells the story of pioneering [[disc jockey]] [[Alan Freed]], who in the 1950s helped introduce and popularize [[rock and roll]], and is often credited with coining the term \"Rock 'n' Roll.\" The film starred [[Tim McIntire]], [[Fran Drescher]], [[Jay Leno]], [[Laraine Newman]], [[Jeff Altman]], and [[Moosie Drier]]. It also featured musical performances by [[Chuck Berry]], [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], [[Frankie Ford]], [[Screamin' Jay Hawkins]], and [[Brooklyn Dreams (group)|Brooklyn Dreams]] as \"Professor La Plano and The Planotones\". The film was not a box-office success.\n  \n[[A&M Records]] released a two-record [[soundtrack album]] featuring the Brooklyn Paramount performances from the movie on record one (in stereo) and original recordings used throughout the film on record two (all in mono). The soundtrack reached number 31 on the ''Billboard'' charts, leaving some to wonder {{who|date = September 2018}} just how that was possible with such meager public exposure.\n\nProducer [[Art Linson]] discusses the movie's production and failure at the box office in his book ''What Just Happened? Bitter Hollywood Tales from the Front Line''.\n\n==Plot==\n\nIn late-1950s New York City, WROL disc jockey Alan Freed (Tim McIntire) promotes his upcoming rock n' roll show at the [[Brooklyn Paramount Theater]], headlined by Chuck Berry and Jerry Lee Lewis. Freed's radio program is hugely popular with teenagers, and the Paramount show is expected to sell out, despite concern that the police will shut it down as they did with Freed's previous show in Boston. Local law enforcement, led by D.A. Coleman (John Lehne), targets Freed for allegedly inciting teenagers to wild and immoral behavior by broadcasting raucous and sexually suggestive rock n' roll songs, many of them by black musicians. WROL station management also dislike Freed's unconventional programming habits, including playing songs that the station has banned such as [[Tutti Frutti (song)|\"Tutti Frutti\"]] by [[Little Richard]]. Freed nevertheless rejects all suggestions that he change his programming style and feature more socially acceptable musical acts, such as [[Pat Boone]]. He also refuses to sign a statement declaring that he never accepted anything in return for playing a record, on the grounds that signing it would be a lie and that all disc jockeys, including those who have signed the statement, take such bribes. \n\nBecause Freed has the power to make a record a hit by playing it on his show, he is constantly besieged by record promoters and artist managers.  He avoids most of these people, but takes an interest in those who share his love for rock n' roll. He repeatedly rebuffs the aggressive record promoter Lennie Richfield (Jeff Altman), but is kind to Artie Moress (Moosie Drier), a young boy who is the president of a [[Buddy Holly]] fan club, and even puts Artie on the air to talk about his idol Holly. Freed also encourages Louise (Laraine Newman), a white teenage songwriter whose parents ignore her talent and disapprove of her associating with the Chesterfields, a black [[doo-wop]] group who perform her songs. Freed himself suffers discrimination when he takes a racially mixed group of teenagers with him to look at a luxury home he wants to buy; the owner refuses to sell to him at any price. Freed's own father back in [[Akron, Ohio]] also rejects him, returning a check Freed sent him and refusing to talk on the telephone with his son. \n\nThe Paramount show goes on despite Coleman's attempts to stop it, including a failed attempt at a drug bust. Louise is moved to tears after the Chesterfields, a late addition to the show, perform her songs to thunderous applause from the capacity crowd. Freed's feisty young secretary Sheryl (Fran Drescher) and his chauffeur Mookie (Jay Leno), who have constantly bickered on the job, finally bond over their shared love of Freed and rock n' roll, and begin a romance. Mid-show, [[IRS]] agents appear and seize all the proceeds from the box office, leaving Freed with no money to pay his artists. However, Chuck Berry saves the day by doing Freed the favor of performing for free. Jerry Lee Lewis, who initially had said he was not coming, then arrives at the last minute and closes the show as the police try to shut it down because teenagers are \"dancing in the aisles\". As the police begin clearing the theater with Lewis still performing onstage, chaos breaks out and the film abruptly ends, with an epilogue stating that this was Freed's last performance, and that he was taken off the air, indicted, moved to California, and died five years later, penniless, but that rock n' roll lives on.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Tim McIntire]]\u2014[[Alan Freed]]\n*[[Fran Drescher]]\u2014Sheryl\n*[[Jay Leno]]\u2014Mookie (Michael)\n*[[Laraine Newman]]\u2014Teenaged Louise\n*[[Moosie Drier]]\u2014Artie Moress\n*[[Jeff Altman]]\u2014Lennie Richfield\n*John Lehne\u2014D.A. Coleman\n*[[Richard Perry]]\u2014Record producer\n\nPerformers\n\n*[[Chuck Berry]]\u2014Himself\n*[[Jerry Lee Lewis]]\u2014Himself\n*[[Screamin' Jay Hawkins]]\u2014Himself\n*[[Frankie Ford]]\u2014Himself\n*Charles Greene\u2014Chuck Otis\n\nThe Chesterfields\n*Carl Earl Weaver\n*Al Chalk\n*Sam Harkness\n*[[Arnold McCuller]]\n\nThe Delights\n*Stephanie Spruill\n*Joyce King\n*Yolanda Howard\n*[[Brenda Russell]]\n\nTimmy and The Tulips (erroneously shown as \"Timmy and The Tangerines\" in the end credits)\n*Charles Irwin\u2014Timmy\n*Jeanne Sheffield\n*[[Jo Ann Harris]]\n\nThe Planotones\n*[[Kenny Vance]]\u2014Professor La Plano\n*[[Joe Esposito (singer)|Joe Esposito]]\n*[[Bruce Sudano]]\n*[[Brooklyn Dreams|Ed Hokenson]]\n\n==Reception==\nThe film was a [[box office bomb]]. However, head of Paramount [[Michael Eisner]] loved the movie and saw it nearly a dozen times.<ref>What to Do for an Encore: CRITIC AT LARGE\nChamplin, Charles. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 07 July 1978: h1.</ref> Critic [[Pauline Kael]] praised the performances and approvingly called the film \"a super [[B-movie]]\" and \"trashily enjoyable\".<ref name=\"Kael\">{{Cite book |last=Kael |first=Pauline |authorlink=Pauline Kael |title=5001 Nights at the Movies |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w4LzeUZ03vQC |year=2011 |origyear=1991 |publisher=Henry Holt and Company |location=New York |isbn=978-1-250-03357-4 |page=22 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that \"'American Hot Wax,' which as a plot so thin you could thread a needle with it, chooses to see the era strictly in terms of the B-movie melodramas it produced.\"<ref>Maslin, Janet (March 17, 1978). \"Screen: 'American Hot Wax'\". ''[[The New York Times]]''. C13.</ref> Arthur D. Murphy of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the film \"unpretentious and enjoyable.\"<ref>Murphy, Arthur D. (March 15, 1978). \"Film Reviews: American Hot Wax\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. 21.</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] gave the film three stars out of four and wrote, \"At its worst, 'Hot Wax' comes off as a 92-minute, 'blasts-from-the-past,' TV record offer ... At its best, the film does manage to suggest some of the frenzied innocence of rock's early days, before rock became a multibillion-dollar industry.\"<ref>Siskel, Gene (March 21, 1978). \"Phonographic memory blurs the 'Hot Wax' facts\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 4, p. 5.</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' found the film \"enjoyable and at times poignant,\" although he noted the film seemed \"evasive\" on the issue of \"Freed's involvement with [[payola]] (a word, incidentally, never heard in the film).\"<ref>Thomas, Kevin (March 17, 1978). \"Freed as a Hero in 'Hot Wax'\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 30.</ref>  Gary Arnold of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote, \"Director Floyd Mutrux and screenwriter John Kaye evidently fail to perceive that the liveliest elements in their movie contradict their admiring view of Freed as a pop-culture hero and martyr ... the filmmakers insist on looking at their subject matter through rose-colored glasses.\"<ref>Arnold, Gary (March 18, 1978). \"'Hot Wax' Waxes Nostalgic\". ''[[The Washington Post]]''. C7.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0077158}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|american-hot-wax|American Hot Wax}}\n{{Jerry Lee Lewis}}\n\n[[Category:1978 films]]\n[[Category:1970s biographical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:American rock music films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about radio people]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Floyd Mutrux]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1959]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1978 film by Floyd Mutrux}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name        = American Hot Wax\n| image       = American Hot Wax.jpg\n| caption     = Theatrical release poster\n| director    = [[Floyd Mutrux]]\n| producer    = [[Art Linson]]\n| screenplay  = [[John Kaye (screenwriter)|John Kaye]]\n| story       = John Kaye<br/>Art Linson\n| starring    = [[Tim McIntire]]<br/>[[Fran Drescher]]<br/>[[Jay Leno]]<br/>[[Laraine Newman]]<br/>[[Moosie Drier]]<br/>[[Jeff Altman]]<br/>John Lehne<br/>[[Richard Perry]]<br/>[[Chuck Berry]]<br/>[[Jerry Lee Lewis]]<br/>[[Screamin' Jay Hawkins]]<br/>[[Frankie Ford]]<br/>Charles Greene\n| editing     = Ronald J. Fagan<br />Melvin Shapiro<br />[[Danford B. Greene]] (sup)\n| cinematography = [[William A. Fraker]]\n| music       = [[Kenny Vance]] \n| studio      = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| distributor = Paramount Pictures\n| runtime     = 91 minutes\n| released    = {{Film date|1978|03|17}}\n| country     = United States\n| language    = English\n| budget      = \n| gross       = $11,000,000<ref name=\"numbers\">[http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/American-Hot-Wax#tab=summary Box Office Information for ''American Hot Wax''.] [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]. Retrieved July 18, 2014.</ref>\n}}\n'''''American Hot Wax''''' is a 1978 [[biographical film]] directed by [[Floyd Mutrux]] with a screenplay [[John Kaye (screenwriter)|John Kaye]] from a story by [[Art Linson]]. The film tells the story of pioneering [[disc jockey]] [[Alan Freed]], who in the 1950s helped introduce and popularize [[rock and roll]], and is often credited with coining the term \"Rock 'n' Roll.\" The film starred [[Tim McIntire]], [[Fran Drescher]], [[Jay Leno]], [[Laraine Newman]], [[Jeff Altman]], and [[Moosie Drier]]. It also featured musical performances by [[Chuck Berry]], [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], [[Frankie Ford]], [[Screamin' Jay Hawkins]], and [[Brooklyn Dreams (group)|Brooklyn Dreams]] as \"Professor La Plano and The Planotones\". The film was not a box-office success.\n  \n[[A&M Records]] released a two-record [[soundtrack album]] featuring the Brooklyn Paramount performances from the movie on record one (in stereo) and original recordings used throughout the film on record two (all in mono). The soundtrack reached number 31 on the ''Billboard'' charts, leaving some to wonder {{who|date = September 2018}} just how that was possible with such meager public exposure.\n\nProducer [[Art Linson]] discusses the movie's production and failure at the box office in his book ''What Just Happened? Bitter Hollywood Tales from the Front Line''.\n\n==Plot==\n\nIn late-1950s New York City, WROL disc jockey Alan Freed (Tim McIntire) promotes his upcoming rock n' roll show at the [[Brooklyn Paramount Theater]], headlined by Chuck Berry and Jerry Lee Lewis. Freed's radio program is hugely popular with teenagers, and the Paramount show is expected to sell out, despite concern that the police will shut it down as they did with Freed's previous show in Boston. Local law enforcement, led by D.A. Coleman (John Lehne), targets Freed for allegedly inciting teenagers to wild and immoral behavior by broadcasting raucous and sexually suggestive rock n' roll songs, many of them by black musicians. WROL station management also dislike Freed's unconventional programming habits, including playing songs that the station has banned such as [[Tutti Frutti (song)|\"Tutti Frutti\"]] by [[Little Richard]]. Freed nevertheless rejects all suggestions that he change his programming style and feature more socially acceptable musical acts, such as [[Pat Boone]]. He also refuses to sign a statement declaring that he never accepted anything in return for playing a record, on the grounds that signing it would be a lie and that all disc jockeys, including those who have signed the statement, take such bribes. \n\nBecause Freed has the power to make a record a hit by playing it on his show, he is constantly besieged by record promoters and artist managers.  He avoids most of these people, but takes an interest in those who share his love for rock n' roll. He repeatedly ignores the aggressive record promoter Lennie Richfield (Jeff Altman), but is kind to Artie Moress (Moosie Drier), a young boy who is the president of a [[Buddy Holly]] fan club, and even puts Artie on the air to talk about his idol Holly. Freed also encourages Louise (Laraine Newman), a white teenage songwriter whose parents ignore her talent and disapprove of her associating with the Chesterfields, a black [[doo-wop]] group who perform her songs. Freed himself suffers discrimination when he takes a racially mixed group of teenagers with him to look at a luxury home he wants to buy; the owner refuses to sell to him at any price. Freed's own father back in [[Akron, Ohio]] also rejects him, returning a check Freed sent him and refusing to talk on the telephone with his son. \n\nThe Paramount show goes on despite Coleman's attempts to stop it, including a failed attempt at a drug bust. Louise is moved to tears after the Chesterfields, a late addition to the show, perform her songs to thunderous applause from the capacity crowd. Freed's feisty young secretary Sheryl (Fran Drescher) and his chauffeur Mookie (Jay Leno), who have constantly bickered on the job, finally bond over their shared love of Freed and rock n' roll, and begin a romance. Mid-show, [[IRS]] agents appear and seize all the proceeds from the box office, leaving Freed with no money to pay his artists. However, Chuck Berry saves the day by doing Freed the favor of performing for free. Jerry Lee Lewis, who initially had said he was not coming, then arrives at the last minute and closes the show as the police try to shut it down because teenagers are \"dancing in the aisles\". As the police begin clearing the theater with Lewis still performing onstage, chaos breaks out and the film abruptly ends, with an epilogue stating that this was Freed's last performance, and that he was taken off the air, indicted, moved to California, and died five years later, penniless, but that rock n' roll lives on.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Tim McIntire]]\u2014[[Alan Freed]]\n*[[Fran Drescher]]\u2014Sheryl\n*[[Jay Leno]]\u2014Mookie (Michael)\n*[[Laraine Newman]]\u2014Teenaged Louise\n*[[Moosie Drier]]\u2014Artie Moress\n*[[Jeff Altman]]\u2014Lennie Richfield\n*John Lehne\u2014D.A. Coleman\n*[[Richard Perry]]\u2014Record producer\n\nPerformers\n\n*[[Chuck Berry]]\u2014Himself\n*[[Jerry Lee Lewis]]\u2014Himself\n*[[Screamin' Jay Hawkins]]\u2014Himself\n*[[Frankie Ford]]\u2014Himself\n*Charles Greene\u2014Chuck Otis\n\nThe Chesterfields\n*Carl Earl Weaver\n*Al Chalk\n*Sam Harkness\n*[[Arnold McCuller]]\n\nThe Delights\n*Stephanie Spruill\n*Joyce King\n*Yolanda Howard\n*[[Brenda Russell]]\n\nTimmy and The Tulips (erroneously shown as \"Timmy and The Tangerines\" in the end credits)\n*Charles Irwin\u2014Timmy\n*Jeanne Sheffield\n*[[Jo Ann Harris]]\n\nThe Planotones\n*[[Kenny Vance]]\u2014Professor La Plano\n*[[Joe Esposito (singer)|Joe Esposito]]\n*[[Bruce Sudano]]\n*[[Brooklyn Dreams|Ed Hokenson]]\n\n==Reception==\nThe film was a [[box office bomb]]. However, head of Paramount [[Michael Eisner]] loved the movie and saw it nearly a dozen times.<ref>What to Do for an Encore: CRITIC AT LARGE\nChamplin, Charles. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 07 July 1978: h1.</ref> Critic [[Pauline Kael]] praised the performances and approvingly called the film \"a super [[B-movie]]\" and \"trashily enjoyable\".<ref name=\"Kael\">{{Cite book |last=Kael |first=Pauline |authorlink=Pauline Kael |title=5001 Nights at the Movies |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w4LzeUZ03vQC |year=2011 |origyear=1991 |publisher=Henry Holt and Company |location=New York |isbn=978-1-250-03357-4 |page=22 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that \"'American Hot Wax,' which as a plot so thin you could thread a needle with it, chooses to see the era strictly in terms of the B-movie melodramas it produced.\"<ref>Maslin, Janet (March 17, 1978). \"Screen: 'American Hot Wax'\". ''[[The New York Times]]''. C13.</ref> Arthur D. Murphy of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the film \"unpretentious and enjoyable.\"<ref>Murphy, Arthur D. (March 15, 1978). \"Film Reviews: American Hot Wax\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. 21.</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] gave the film three stars out of four and wrote, \"At its worst, 'Hot Wax' comes off as a 92-minute, 'blasts-from-the-past,' TV record offer ... At its best, the film does manage to suggest some of the frenzied innocence of rock's early days, before rock became a multibillion-dollar industry.\"<ref>Siskel, Gene (March 21, 1978). \"Phonographic memory blurs the 'Hot Wax' facts\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 4, p. 5.</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' found the film \"enjoyable and at times poignant,\" although he noted the film seemed \"evasive\" on the issue of \"Freed's involvement with [[payola]] (a word, incidentally, never heard in the film).\"<ref>Thomas, Kevin (March 17, 1978). \"Freed as a Hero in 'Hot Wax'\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 30.</ref>  Gary Arnold of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote, \"Director Floyd Mutrux and screenwriter John Kaye evidently fail to perceive that the liveliest elements in their movie contradict their admiring view of Freed as a pop-culture hero and martyr ... the filmmakers insist on looking at their subject matter through rose-colored glasses.\"<ref>Arnold, Gary (March 18, 1978). \"'Hot Wax' Waxes Nostalgic\". ''[[The Washington Post]]''. C7.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0077158}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|american-hot-wax|American Hot Wax}}\n{{Jerry Lee Lewis}}\n\n[[Category:1978 films]]\n[[Category:1970s biographical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:American rock music films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about radio people]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Floyd Mutrux]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1959]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "TheBlinkster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Hot_Wax"}
{"title_page": "Welsh rarebit", "text_new": "{{for|the radio variety show|Welsh Rarebit (radio programme)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name            = Welsh rabbit\n| image           = Welsh rarebit.JPG\n| image_size      = 300\n| caption         = \n| alternate_name  = Welsh rarebit (folk etymology)\n| country         = [[Wales]]\n| region          = \n| creator         = \n| course          = \n| type            = [[Savoury (small dish)|Savoury]]\n| served          = \n| main_ingredient = \n| variations      = Buck Rabbit, Blushing Bunny, [[Hot Brown]]\n| calories        = \n| other           = \n}}\n'''Welsh rabbit''' (original spelling) or '''Welsh rarebit''' (spelling based on [[folk etymology]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/welsh%20rabbit|title=Welsh Rabbit - Definition of Welsh rabbit by Merriam-Webster|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/Welsh-rarebit |title=Welsh rarebit - definition of Welsh rarebit in English from the Oxford dictionary |publisher=}}</ref> is a traditional [[Welsh cuisine|Welsh dish]] made with a savoury [[sauce]] of melted [[cheese]] and various other ingredients and served hot, after being poured over slices (or other pieces) of [[toast]]ed [[bread]] or served in a [[chafing dish]] like a [[fondue]].<ref name=\"SpryHume\" /> The names of the dish originate from 18th-century Britain.<ref name=\"oed\" /> Despite these, the dish contains no rabbit meat.  More often described with suffixes or choice of extras on menus, variants have been named ''English rabbit, Scotch rabbit, buck rabbit, golden buck, blushing bunny'' and in some parts of France it is known as ''{{lang|fr|le/un Welsh}}''.\n\n==Sauce==\n\nIts recipes include the addition of [[ale]], [[mustard (condiment)|mustard]], ground [[cayenne pepper]], [[paprika]]<ref name=\"LeGuide\">''[[Le Guide Culinaire]]'' by Georges Auguste [[Escoffier]], translated by H. L. Cracknell and R. J. Kaufmann</ref><ref>''[[Le R\u00e9pertoire de la Cuisine]]'' by [[Louis Saulnier]], translated by E. Brunet.</ref><ref>''Hering's Dictionary of Classical and Modern Cookery'', edited and translated by Walter Bickel</ref> wine and/or [[Worcestershire sauce]].<ref>Recipes published on the labels of [[Lea and Perrins]] ([[H. J. Heinz Company|Heinz]]) Worcestershire sauce,</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://graphic-design.tjs-labs.com/show-picture?id=1093969680|title=\"It takes more than beer to make a perfect rarebit\"|publisher=}}</ref> The sauce may also blend cheese and mustard into a [[B\u00e9chamel sauce]].<ref name=\"SpryHume\">The Constance Spry Cookery Book by [[Constance Spry|Constance Spry and Rosemary Hume]]</ref><ref name=\"bcscb\">[[Fannie Farmer|Farmer, Fannie M.]], ''[[Boston Cooking-School Cook Book]]'' Boston, 1896, {{ISBN|0-451-12892-3}}</ref> Some recipes have become textbook [[savoury (small dish)|savouries]] listed by culinary authorities including [[Auguste Escoffier]], [[Louis Saulnier]] and others, who tend to use the form Welsh ''rarebit'', more strongly communicating to a non-English audience that it is not a meat dish.\n\nAcknowledging that there is more than one way for its making, cookbooks have included two recipes: the ''[[Boston Cooking-School Cook Book]]'' of 1896 provides one b\u00e9chamel-based recipe and another with beer;<ref name=\"bcscb\" /> ''[[Le Guide Culinaire]]'' of 1907 has one with ale and one without;<ref name=\"LeGuide\" /> the ''[[Constance Spry]] Cookery Book'' of 1956 has one with flour and one without.<ref name=\"SpryHume\" />\n\n==Variants==\n[[Hannah Glasse]], in her 1747 [[cookbook]] ''[[The Art of Cookery]]'', gives close variants \"Scotch rabbit\", \"Welsh rabbit\" and two versions of \"English rabbit\".<ref>[[Hannah Glasse|Glasse, Hannah]], ''The Art of Cookery made Plain and Easy, ...by a Lady'' (Posthumous edition, L. Wangford, London, c. 1770), p. 146. [https://archive.org/stream/artcookerymadep02glasgoog#page/n232/mode/2up Online 1774 edition read here]</ref>\n\n<blockquote><p>To make a ''Scotch rabbit'', toast the bread very nicely on both sides, butter it, cut a slice of cheese about as big as the bread, toast it on both sides, and lay it on the bread.\n\n<p>To make a ''Welsh rabbit'', toast the bread on both sides, then toast the cheese on one side, lay it on the toast, and with a hot iron brown the other side. You may rub it over with mustard.\n\n<p>To make an ''English rabbit'', toast the bread brown on both sides, lay it in a plate before the fire, pour a glass of red wine over it, and let it soak the wine up. Then cut some cheese very thin and lay it very thick over the bread, put it in a tin oven before the fire, and it will be toasted and browned presently. Serve it always hot.\n\n<p>Or do it thus. Toast the bread and soak it in the wine, set it before the fire, rub butter over the bottom of a plate, lay the cheese on, pour in two or three spoonfuls of white wine, cover it with another plate, set it over a chafing-dish of hot coals for two or three minutes, then stir it till it is done and well mixed. You may stir in a little mustard; when it enough lays it on the bread, just brown it with a hot shovel.</blockquote>\n\n[[File:Welsh rarebit with an egg.JPG|thumb|Buck rarebit (Welsh rarebit with an egg)]]\n\nServed with an egg on top, it makes a ''buck rabbit''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/buck-rabbit|title=Definition of \"buck rabbit\" - Collins English Dictionary|publisher=}}</ref> or a ''golden buck''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/golden%20buck|title=Golden Buck - Definition of Golden buck by Merriam-Webster|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWelsh rarebit blended with tomato (or tomato soup) makes a ''blushing bunny''.<ref>Lily Haxworth Wallace, Rumford Chemical Works, ''The Rumford complete cookbook'', 1908, [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_BFsEAAAAYAAJ/page/n215 full text, p. 196]</ref>\n\nIts analogue ''{{lang|fr|le/un Welsh}}'' is traditionally served in Nord-Pas-de-Calais,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-36665190|title=Wales fans try the French Welsh rarebit|first=Max|last=Evans|date=30 June 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and [[C\u00f4te d'Opale]] French regions.\n\n==Origin==\nThe first recorded reference to the dish was \"Welsh rabbit\" in 1725, but the origin of the term is unknown.<ref name=oed>[[Oxford English Dictionary]], Second Edition, 1989.</ref>\n\nThere is some suggestion that it derives from a [[South Wales Valleys]] staple, in which a generous lump of cheese is placed into a mixture of beaten eggs and milk, seasoned with salt and pepper, and baked in the oven until the egg mixture has firmed and the cheese has melted. [[Onion]] may be added and the mixture would be eaten with bread and butter and occasionally with the vinegar from pickled [[beetroot]].<ref>Stephens, M, 1986. Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales, OUP</ref><ref>Written recollections of the artist John Selway, 2013</ref>\n\n===Welsh===\nThe word ''Welsh'' may have been adopted because it carries a now-archaic sense in [[English people|English]] to mean \"foreign, non-native\" \u2014 an etymological phenomenon seen in its ultimate ancestor, the [[Proto-Germanic]] ''[[walhaz]]'' (\"foreigner\") and many of its descendants like the dated sense of [[German language|German]] {{wiktang|welsch}} ([[Romance language|Romance]]-speaker).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=Welsh|title=Online Etymology Dictionary|publisher=}}</ref> It is also possible that the dish was attributed to the [[Welsh people|Welsh]] because they were considered particularly fond of cheese, as evidenced by [[Andrew Boorde]] in his ''Fyrst Boke of the Introduction of Knowledge'' (1542), writing \"I am a Welshman, I do love cause boby, good roasted cheese.\"<ref>[[Andrew Boorde]]: ''The Fyrst Boke of the Introduction of Knowledge, the which do the teache a man to speak part of all manner of languages, and to know the usage and fashion of all manner of countreys'' (1542)</ref> Here \"cause boby\" is the Welsh ''{{lang|cy|caws pobi}}'', meaning \"baked cheese\", but whether it implies a recipe like Welsh rarebit is a matter of speculation.\n\n===Rarebit===\nThe word ''rarebit'' is a corruption of ''rabbit'', \"Welsh rabbit\" being first recorded in 1725 and the variant \"Welsh rarebit\" being first recorded in 1785 by [[Francis Grose]]. According to the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', 'Welsh rarebit' is an \"etymologiz<!-- Oxford spelling -->ing alteration. There is no evidence of the independent use of rarebit\". The word ''rarebit'' has no other use than in Welsh rabbit.<ref name=oed/><ref>The Concise Oxford English Dictionary, 11th edition (2006)</ref>\n\n\"Eighteenth-century English cookbooks reveal that it was then considered to be a luscious supper or [[tavern]] dish, based on the fine cheddar-type cheeses and the wheat bread [...] . Surprisingly, it seems there was not only a Welsh Rabbit, but also an English Rabbit, an Irish and a Scotch Rabbit, but nary a rarebit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalofantiques.com/hearthmay.htm|title=Hunting The Welch Rabbit, Hearth to Hearth Article, JOA&C May 2000 Issue|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe entry in [[Merriam-Webster]]'s ''Dictionary of English Usage'' is \"Welsh rabbit, Welsh rarebit\" and states: \"When Francis Grose defined Welsh rabbit in ''A Classical Dictionary of the Vulgar Tongue'' in 1785, he mistakenly indicated that rabbit was a corruption of ''rarebit''. It is not certain that this erroneous idea originated with Grose....\"<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2yJusP0vrdgC&pg=RA3-PA952&dq=%22welsh+rabbit%22&sig=l5yBOfuSWhBHXwFRBCl_Q8MVGPw Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage, p. 592] at books.google.com (accessed 9 November 2007)</ref>\n\nIn his 1926 edition of the ''Dictionary of Modern English Usage'' ([[Fowler's]] style guide) grammarian [[H. W. Fowler]] opines: \"Welsh Rabbit is amusing and right. Welsh Rarebit is stupid and wrong.\"<ref>Fowler, H. W., [[A Dictionary of Modern English Usage]], Oxford University Press, 1926</ref>\n\n==In culture==\nThe notion that toasted cheese was a favourite dish irresistible to the Welsh has existed since the Middle Ages. In ''[[Shakespeare's Jest Book|A C Merie Talys]]'' (100 Merry Tales), a printed book of jokes of 1526 AD (of which [[William Shakespeare]] made some use), it is told that God became weary of all the Welshmen in [[Heaven]], 'which with their krakynge and babelynge trobelyd all the others', and asked the Porter of Heaven Gate, St Peter, to do something about it. So St Peter went outside the gates and called in a loud voice, '''Cause bobe'', yt is as moche to say as ''rostyd chese''<nowiki/>', at which all the Welshmen ran out, and when St Peter saw they were all outside, he went in and locked the gates, which is why there are no Welshmen in heaven. The 1526 compiler says he found this story 'Wryten amonge olde gestys'.<ref>In two known editions, one undated. W. Carew Hazlitt (Ed.), ''A Hundred Merry Tales: The Earliest English Jest-Book'', facsimile (privately published, 1887), fol xxi, verso [https://archive.org/stream/hundredmerrytale00hazl#page/n87/mode/2up Read here]. See also Hermann Oesterley (Ed.), ''Shakespeare's Jest Book. A Hundred Mery Talys, from the only perfect copy known'' (London 1866).</ref>\n\nA legend mentioned in [[Betty Crocker|''Betty Crocker's Cookbook'']] claims that Welsh peasants were not allowed to eat rabbits caught in hunts on the estates of the [[nobility]], so they used melted cheese as a substitute. The author also claims that [[Ben Jonson]] and [[Charles Dickens]] ate Welsh rarebit at [[Ye Olde Cheshire Cheese]], a pub in London.<ref>{{cite book | title=Betty Crocker's Cookbook | year=1989 | page=184 | publisher=Prentice Hall}}</ref> There is no good evidence for any of this; what is more, Ben Jonson died almost a century before the term Welsh rabbit is first attested.<ref name=\"oed\"/>\n\nAccording to the American satirist [[Ambrose Bierce]], the continued use of ''rarebit'' was an attempt to rationalise the absence of rabbit, writing in his 1911 ''Devil's Dictionary'': \"RAREBIT n. A Welsh rabbit, in the speech of the humorless, who point out that it is not a rabbit. To whom it may be solemnly explained that the comestible known as [[toad in the hole]] is really not a toad, and that ''[[ris de veau]] \u00e0 la financi\u00e8re'' is not the smile of a calf prepared after the recipe of a she-banker.\"<ref>''[[Devil's Dictionary]]'' by [[Ambrose Bierce]], 1911</ref>\n\nIn H. G. Wells's 1898 short story \"[[The Man Who Could Work Miracles (story)|The Man Who Could Work Miracles]]\" Mr. Fotheringay helps himself to a couple of Welsh rarebits \"out of vacancy\".\n\nThe comic strip \"[[Dream of the Rarebit Fiend]]\", by [[Winsor McCay]], featured the fantastic dreams that various characters had because they ate a Welsh rarebit before going to bed.\n\nIn \"Gomer, the Welsh Rarebit Fiend\", Season 3 Episode 24 of ''[[Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.]]'', indulging in Welsh rarebit causes Gomer (and later Sgt. Carter) to sleepwalk.\n\nIn the [[Neil Simon]] play ''[[Plaza Suite]]'', in Act I, character Karen Nash offers Miss McCormack a Welsh rarebit, in an effort to disrupt an impromptu meeting between her and Sam Nash, Karen's husband.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/plazasuitecomedy0000simo|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/plazasuitecomedy0000simo/page/31 31]|quote=neil simon plaza suite rarebit.|title=Plaza Suite: A Comedy in Three Acts|last=Simon|first=Neil|date=1969|publisher=Samuel French, Inc.|isbn=9780573614071|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the film ''[[Phantom Thread]]'' (Paul Thomas Anderson, 2017), Reynolds Woodcock orders a Welsh rarebit for breakfast with a poached egg, bacon, scones, butter, jam (not strawberry), sausages and Lapsang tea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonappetit.com/story/phantom-thread-breakfast-scene|title=If There Was an Oscar for Best Food Scene, This Would Win|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Bon App\u00e9tit|language=en|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref>\n\nIn the first book of the [[The Hardy Boys|Hardy Boys]] mystery stories, ''[[The Tower Treasure]]'' (1927), on page 25, Chet offers to make a side dish of Welsh Rabbit.\n\n==See also==\n{{wiktionary|Welsh rarebit|Welsh rabbit|rarebit}}\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Food}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Dream of the Rarebit Fiend]]''\n* [[List of Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C. episodes#Season 3 (1966\u201367)|Gomer, the Welsh Rarebit Fiend]]\n* [[Beer soup]]\n* [[Cheese on toast]]\n* [[Cheese roll]]\n* [[Croque-monsieur]] and [[croque-madame]]\n* [[Hot Brown]]\n* [[Jiggs dinner]]\n* [[List of cheese dishes]]\n* [[Mollete]]\n* [[List of Sandwiches]]\n** [[Dagwood sandwich]]\n** [[Grilled cheese sandwich]]\n** [[Horseshoe sandwich]]\n** [[Monte Cristo sandwich]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|28em}}\n\n{{Cheese dishes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Welsh Rarebit}}\n[[Category:British cuisine]]\n[[Category:British snack foods]]\n[[Category:Cheese dishes]]\n[[Category:Toast dishes]]\n[[Category:Welsh cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the radio variety show|Welsh Rarebit (radio programme)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name            = Welsh rabbit\n| image           = Rarebit loz.png\n| image_size      = 300\n| caption         = \n| alternate_name  = Welsh rarebit (folk etymology)\n| country         = [[Wales]]\n| region          = \n| creator         = \n| course          = \n| type            = [[Savoury (small dish)|Savoury]]\n| served          = \n| main_ingredient = \n| variations      = Buck Rabbit, Blushing Bunny, [[Hot Brown]]\n| calories        = \n| other           = \n}}\n'''Welsh rabbit''' (original spelling) or '''Welsh rarebit''' (spelling based on [[folk etymology]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/welsh%20rabbit|title=Welsh Rabbit - Definition of Welsh rabbit by Merriam-Webster|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/Welsh-rarebit |title=Welsh rarebit - definition of Welsh rarebit in English from the Oxford dictionary |publisher=}}</ref> is a traditional [[Welsh cuisine|Welsh dish]] made with a savoury [[sauce]] of melted [[cheese]] and various other ingredients and served hot, after being poured over slices (or other pieces) of [[toast]]ed [[bread]] or served in a [[chafing dish]] like a [[fondue]].<ref name=\"SpryHume\" /> The names of the dish originate from 18th-century Britain.<ref name=\"oed\" /> Despite these, the dish contains no rabbit meat.  More often described with suffixes or choice of extras on menus, variants have been named ''English rabbit, Scotch rabbit, buck rabbit, golden buck, blushing bunny'' and in some parts of France it is known as ''{{lang|fr|le/un Welsh}}''.\n\n==Sauce==\n\nIts recipes include the addition of [[ale]], [[mustard (condiment)|mustard]], ground [[cayenne pepper]], [[paprika]]<ref name=\"LeGuide\">''[[Le Guide Culinaire]]'' by Georges Auguste [[Escoffier]], translated by H. L. Cracknell and R. J. Kaufmann</ref><ref>''[[Le R\u00e9pertoire de la Cuisine]]'' by [[Louis Saulnier]], translated by E. Brunet.</ref><ref>''Hering's Dictionary of Classical and Modern Cookery'', edited and translated by Walter Bickel</ref> wine and/or [[Worcestershire sauce]].<ref>Recipes published on the labels of [[Lea and Perrins]] ([[H. J. Heinz Company|Heinz]]) Worcestershire sauce,</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://graphic-design.tjs-labs.com/show-picture?id=1093969680|title=\"It takes more than beer to make a perfect rarebit\"|publisher=}}</ref> The sauce may also blend cheese and mustard into a [[B\u00e9chamel sauce]].<ref name=\"SpryHume\">The Constance Spry Cookery Book by [[Constance Spry|Constance Spry and Rosemary Hume]]</ref><ref name=\"bcscb\">[[Fannie Farmer|Farmer, Fannie M.]], ''[[Boston Cooking-School Cook Book]]'' Boston, 1896, {{ISBN|0-451-12892-3}}</ref> Some recipes have become textbook [[savoury (small dish)|savouries]] listed by culinary authorities including [[Auguste Escoffier]], [[Louis Saulnier]] and others, who tend to use the form Welsh ''rarebit'', more strongly communicating to a non-English audience that it is not a meat dish.\n\nAcknowledging that there is more than one way for its making, cookbooks have included two recipes: the ''[[Boston Cooking-School Cook Book]]'' of 1896 provides one b\u00e9chamel-based recipe and another with beer;<ref name=\"bcscb\" /> ''[[Le Guide Culinaire]]'' of 1907 has one with ale and one without;<ref name=\"LeGuide\" /> the ''[[Constance Spry]] Cookery Book'' of 1956 has one with flour and one without.<ref name=\"SpryHume\" />\n\n==Variants==\n[[Hannah Glasse]], in her 1747 [[cookbook]] ''[[The Art of Cookery]]'', gives close variants \"Scotch rabbit\", \"Welsh rabbit\" and two versions of \"English rabbit\".<ref>[[Hannah Glasse|Glasse, Hannah]], ''The Art of Cookery made Plain and Easy, ...by a Lady'' (Posthumous edition, L. Wangford, London, c. 1770), p. 146. [https://archive.org/stream/artcookerymadep02glasgoog#page/n232/mode/2up Online 1774 edition read here]</ref>\n\n<blockquote><p>To make a ''Scotch rabbit'', toast the bread very nicely on both sides, butter it, cut a slice of cheese about as big as the bread, toast it on both sides, and lay it on the bread.\n\n<p>To make a ''Welsh rabbit'', toast the bread on both sides, then toast the cheese on one side, lay it on the toast, and with a hot iron brown the other side. You may rub it over with mustard.\n\n<p>To make an ''English rabbit'', toast the bread brown on both sides, lay it in a plate before the fire, pour a glass of red wine over it, and let it soak the wine up. Then cut some cheese very thin and lay it very thick over the bread, put it in a tin oven before the fire, and it will be toasted and browned presently. Serve it always hot.\n\n<p>Or do it thus. Toast the bread and soak it in the wine, set it before the fire, rub butter over the bottom of a plate, lay the cheese on, pour in two or three spoonfuls of white wine, cover it with another plate, set it over a chafing-dish of hot coals for two or three minutes, then stir it till it is done and well mixed. You may stir in a little mustard; when it enough lays it on the bread, just brown it with a hot shovel.</blockquote>\n\n[[File:Welsh rarebit with an egg.JPG|thumb|Buck rarebit (Welsh rarebit with an egg)]]\n\nServed with an egg on top, it makes a ''buck rabbit''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/buck-rabbit|title=Definition of \"buck rabbit\" - Collins English Dictionary|publisher=}}</ref> or a ''golden buck''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/golden%20buck|title=Golden Buck - Definition of Golden buck by Merriam-Webster|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWelsh rarebit blended with tomato (or tomato soup) makes a ''blushing bunny''.<ref>Lily Haxworth Wallace, Rumford Chemical Works, ''The Rumford complete cookbook'', 1908, [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_BFsEAAAAYAAJ/page/n215 full text, p. 196]</ref>\n\nIts analogue ''{{lang|fr|le/un Welsh}}'' is traditionally served in Nord-Pas-de-Calais,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-36665190|title=Wales fans try the French Welsh rarebit|first=Max|last=Evans|date=30 June 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and [[C\u00f4te d'Opale]] French regions.\n\n==Origin==\nThe first recorded reference to the dish was \"Welsh rabbit\" in 1725, but the origin of the term is unknown.<ref name=oed>[[Oxford English Dictionary]], Second Edition, 1989.</ref>\n\nThere is some suggestion that it derives from a [[South Wales Valleys]] staple, in which a generous lump of cheese is placed into a mixture of beaten eggs and milk, seasoned with salt and pepper, and baked in the oven until the egg mixture has firmed and the cheese has melted. [[Onion]] may be added and the mixture would be eaten with bread and butter and occasionally with the vinegar from pickled [[beetroot]].<ref>Stephens, M, 1986. Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales, OUP</ref><ref>Written recollections of the artist John Selway, 2013</ref>\n\n===Welsh===\nThe word ''Welsh'' may have been adopted because it carries a now-archaic sense in [[English people|English]] to mean \"foreign, non-native\" \u2014 an etymological phenomenon seen in its ultimate ancestor, the [[Proto-Germanic]] ''[[walhaz]]'' (\"foreigner\") and many of its descendants like the dated sense of [[German language|German]] {{wiktang|welsch}} ([[Romance language|Romance]]-speaker).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=Welsh|title=Online Etymology Dictionary|publisher=}}</ref> It is also possible that the dish was attributed to the [[Welsh people|Welsh]] because they were considered particularly fond of cheese, as evidenced by [[Andrew Boorde]] in his ''Fyrst Boke of the Introduction of Knowledge'' (1542), writing \"I am a Welshman, I do love cause boby, good roasted cheese.\"<ref>[[Andrew Boorde]]: ''The Fyrst Boke of the Introduction of Knowledge, the which do the teache a man to speak part of all manner of languages, and to know the usage and fashion of all manner of countreys'' (1542)</ref> Here \"cause boby\" is the Welsh ''{{lang|cy|caws pobi}}'', meaning \"baked cheese\", but whether it implies a recipe like Welsh rarebit is a matter of speculation.\n\n===Rarebit===\nThe word ''rarebit'' is a corruption of ''rabbit'', \"Welsh rabbit\" being first recorded in 1725 and the variant \"Welsh rarebit\" being first recorded in 1785 by [[Francis Grose]]. According to the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', 'Welsh rarebit' is an \"etymologiz<!-- Oxford spelling -->ing alteration. There is no evidence of the independent use of rarebit\". The word ''rarebit'' has no other use than in Welsh rabbit.<ref name=oed/><ref>The Concise Oxford English Dictionary, 11th edition (2006)</ref>\n\n\"Eighteenth-century English cookbooks reveal that it was then considered to be a luscious supper or [[tavern]] dish, based on the fine cheddar-type cheeses and the wheat bread [...] . Surprisingly, it seems there was not only a Welsh Rabbit, but also an English Rabbit, an Irish and a Scotch Rabbit, but nary a rarebit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalofantiques.com/hearthmay.htm|title=Hunting The Welch Rabbit, Hearth to Hearth Article, JOA&C May 2000 Issue|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe entry in [[Merriam-Webster]]'s ''Dictionary of English Usage'' is \"Welsh rabbit, Welsh rarebit\" and states: \"When Francis Grose defined Welsh rabbit in ''A Classical Dictionary of the Vulgar Tongue'' in 1785, he mistakenly indicated that rabbit was a corruption of ''rarebit''. It is not certain that this erroneous idea originated with Grose....\"<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2yJusP0vrdgC&pg=RA3-PA952&dq=%22welsh+rabbit%22&sig=l5yBOfuSWhBHXwFRBCl_Q8MVGPw Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage, p. 592] at books.google.com (accessed 9 November 2007)</ref>\n\nIn his 1926 edition of the ''Dictionary of Modern English Usage'' ([[Fowler's]] style guide) grammarian [[H. W. Fowler]] opines: \"Welsh Rabbit is amusing and right. Welsh Rarebit is stupid and wrong.\"<ref>Fowler, H. W., [[A Dictionary of Modern English Usage]], Oxford University Press, 1926</ref>\n\n==In culture==\nThe notion that toasted cheese was a favourite dish irresistible to the Welsh has existed since the Middle Ages. In ''[[Shakespeare's Jest Book|A C Merie Talys]]'' (100 Merry Tales), a printed book of jokes of 1526 AD (of which [[William Shakespeare]] made some use), it is told that God became weary of all the Welshmen in [[Heaven]], 'which with their krakynge and babelynge trobelyd all the others', and asked the Porter of Heaven Gate, St Peter, to do something about it. So St Peter went outside the gates and called in a loud voice, '''Cause bobe'', yt is as moche to say as ''rostyd chese''<nowiki/>', at which all the Welshmen ran out, and when St Peter saw they were all outside, he went in and locked the gates, which is why there are no Welshmen in heaven. The 1526 compiler says he found this story 'Wryten amonge olde gestys'.<ref>In two known editions, one undated. W. Carew Hazlitt (Ed.), ''A Hundred Merry Tales: The Earliest English Jest-Book'', facsimile (privately published, 1887), fol xxi, verso [https://archive.org/stream/hundredmerrytale00hazl#page/n87/mode/2up Read here]. See also Hermann Oesterley (Ed.), ''Shakespeare's Jest Book. A Hundred Mery Talys, from the only perfect copy known'' (London 1866).</ref>\n\nA legend mentioned in [[Betty Crocker|''Betty Crocker's Cookbook'']] claims that Welsh peasants were not allowed to eat rabbits caught in hunts on the estates of the [[nobility]], so they used melted cheese as a substitute. The author also claims that [[Ben Jonson]] and [[Charles Dickens]] ate Welsh rarebit at [[Ye Olde Cheshire Cheese]], a pub in London.<ref>{{cite book | title=Betty Crocker's Cookbook | year=1989 | page=184 | publisher=Prentice Hall}}</ref> There is no good evidence for any of this; what is more, Ben Jonson died almost a century before the term Welsh rabbit is first attested.<ref name=\"oed\"/>\n\nAccording to the American satirist [[Ambrose Bierce]], the continued use of ''rarebit'' was an attempt to rationalise the absence of rabbit, writing in his 1911 ''Devil's Dictionary'': \"RAREBIT n. A Welsh rabbit, in the speech of the humorless, who point out that it is not a rabbit. To whom it may be solemnly explained that the comestible known as [[toad in the hole]] is really not a toad, and that ''[[ris de veau]] \u00e0 la financi\u00e8re'' is not the smile of a calf prepared after the recipe of a she-banker.\"<ref>''[[Devil's Dictionary]]'' by [[Ambrose Bierce]], 1911</ref>\n\nIn H. G. Wells's 1898 short story \"[[The Man Who Could Work Miracles (story)|The Man Who Could Work Miracles]]\" Mr. Fotheringay helps himself to a couple of Welsh rarebits \"out of vacancy\".\n\nThe comic strip \"[[Dream of the Rarebit Fiend]]\", by [[Winsor McCay]], featured the fantastic dreams that various characters had because they ate a Welsh rarebit before going to bed.\n\nIn \"Gomer, the Welsh Rarebit Fiend\", Season 3 Episode 24 of ''[[Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.]]'', indulging in Welsh rarebit causes Gomer (and later Sgt. Carter) to sleepwalk.\n\nIn the [[Neil Simon]] play ''[[Plaza Suite]]'', in Act I, character Karen Nash offers Miss McCormack a Welsh rarebit, in an effort to disrupt an impromptu meeting between her and Sam Nash, Karen's husband.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/plazasuitecomedy0000simo|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/plazasuitecomedy0000simo/page/31 31]|quote=neil simon plaza suite rarebit.|title=Plaza Suite: A Comedy in Three Acts|last=Simon|first=Neil|date=1969|publisher=Samuel French, Inc.|isbn=9780573614071|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the film ''[[Phantom Thread]]'' (Paul Thomas Anderson, 2017), Reynolds Woodcock orders a Welsh rarebit for breakfast with a poached egg, bacon, scones, butter, jam (not strawberry), sausages and Lapsang tea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonappetit.com/story/phantom-thread-breakfast-scene|title=If There Was an Oscar for Best Food Scene, This Would Win|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Bon App\u00e9tit|language=en|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref>\n\nIn the first book of the [[The Hardy Boys|Hardy Boys]] mystery stories, ''[[The Tower Treasure]]'' (1927), on page 25, Chet offers to make a side dish of Welsh Rabbit.\n\n==See also==\n{{wiktionary|Welsh rarebit|Welsh rabbit|rarebit}}\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Food}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Dream of the Rarebit Fiend]]''\n* [[List of Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C. episodes#Season 3 (1966\u201367)|Gomer, the Welsh Rarebit Fiend]]\n* [[Beer soup]]\n* [[Cheese on toast]]\n* [[Cheese roll]]\n* [[Croque-monsieur]] and [[croque-madame]]\n* [[Hot Brown]]\n* [[Jiggs dinner]]\n* [[List of cheese dishes]]\n* [[Mollete]]\n* [[List of Sandwiches]]\n** [[Dagwood sandwich]]\n** [[Grilled cheese sandwich]]\n** [[Horseshoe sandwich]]\n** [[Monte Cristo sandwich]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|28em}}\n\n{{Cheese dishes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Welsh Rarebit}}\n[[Category:British cuisine]]\n[[Category:British snack foods]]\n[[Category:Cheese dishes]]\n[[Category:Toast dishes]]\n[[Category:Welsh cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "Philafrenzy", "label": "safe", "comment": "CE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welsh_rarebit"}
{"title_page": "Holly Short", "text_new": "{{Infobox character\n| name        = Holly Short\n| series      = [[Artemis Fowl]]\n| image       = HollyMediumCloseup.png\n| image_size  = 150px\n| caption     = Holly Short as depicted in ''[[Artemis Fowl: The Graphic Novel]]''\n| first       = ''[[Artemis Fowl (novel)|Artemis Fowl]]''\n| last        = ''[[The Fowl Twins]]''\n| creator     = [[Eoin Colfer]]\n| portrayer   = [[Lara McDonnell]]\n| species     = Elf\n| gender      = Female\n| occupation  = Captain of the [[Lower Elements Police#LEPrecon|LEPrecon]]<br>Commodore (''The Fowl Twins'')\n}}\n'''Captain Holly Short''' is a character of the ''[[Artemis Fowl]]'' novel series by [[Eoin Colfer]].\n\n==Character outline==\nHolly Short is a weird and quirky [[Elf (Artemis Fowl)|elf]] with an auburn [[crew cut]] (although she later grows a fringe) and 1 hazel and 1 blue eye, as well as the pointy ears typical of her species and nut-brown skin of a [[coffee]] complexion. She stands at one meter in height (said to be three feet in US editions), one centimeter shorter than the [[Fairy (Artemis Fowl)|fairy]] average (an inch shorter in US editions), and has a gymnast-like stance. Like all elves, she is child-sized by human standards, but her bodily proportions are adult. According to ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Arctic Incident]]'', Holly is about eighty years old (Elves and other magic species live much longer than humans. It is said that there is a dwarf over 2000 years old in the book).<ref name=\"Opal Deception\">{{cite book| last = Colfer| first = Eoin| title = Artemis Fowl and the Opal Deception| series = Artemis Fowl| date = 30 April 2005| publisher = Puffin Books| location = New York| isbn = 978-0-14-138164-0| page = 107| chapter = Narrow Escapes }}</ref> Holly is the first and only female captain in the organization [[Lower Elements Police#LEPrecon|LEPrecon]]. In ''[[The Artemis Fowl Files]]'', she notes that she eventually earns the respect of her male colleagues. Holly will defy the orders of superiors and disobey rules if she believes that she can be of more help that way, and has gotten into trouble multiple times for defying a direct command.<ref name=\"AFFiles\">{{cite book| last = Colfer| first = Eoin| title = The Artemis Fowl Files| series = Artemis Fowl| date = 2005-11-05| publisher = Hyperion Books for Children| location = New York| isbn = 978-1-4231-0044-7| pages = [https://archive.org/details/artmisfowlfiles00eoin/page/86 86\u201387]| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/artmisfowlfiles00eoin/page/86}}</ref> She is described as pretty, but in a dangerous way, comparable to a [[Latrodectus|black widow]]. Her interests include playing the fairy game \"Crunchball\", reading (especially thrillers), and flying with artificial wings.<ref name=\"AFFiles\" />\n\nHolly lost her father at a young age. Her mother, Coral Short, is described as a European elf who was temperamental and had an appearance similar to Holly's. ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Time Paradox]]'' reveals that her mother worked in [[Lower Elements Police]] division \"LEPmarine\" and died after she was exposed to dirty radiation, which is poisonous to fairies.<ref name=\"TimeParadox\">{{cite book|last=Colfer|first=Eoin|title=Artemis Fowl: The Time Paradox|url=https://archive.org/details/artemisfowltimep00colf|url-access=registration|publisher=Hyperion Books for Children|location=New York|date=July 2008|series=Artemis Fowl|pages=[https://archive.org/details/artemisfowltimep00colf/page/48 48\u201349]|isbn=978-1-4231-0836-8 }}</ref>\n\nAfter ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Opal Deception]]'', Holly quits the LEP because the new LEP commander, Ark Sool mentions that he will keep a close eye on her to catch any faults and she begins to work with [[Mulch Diggums]].\n\nHowever, after working as a private detective with Mulch for a short time, she returns to the Section 8 unit of the LEP in ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Lost Colony]]'', in time to get Artemis, Butler and the others out of trouble.\n\nHer relationship with Artemis Fowl has changed dramatically since the beginning of the series, morphing from hostility to grudging respect to friendship, and has recently included substantial hints of a romantic attraction despite the species and age gap (the mental age gap being closed in ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Lost Colony]]'' and physical age gap briefly being closed for ''Artemis Fowl and the The Time Paradox'', both via extensive [[time travel]]).\n\n==Appearances==\n===In ''Artemis Fowl''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl (novel)|Artemis Fowl]]'', Holly is abducted by 125-year-old criminal mastermind [[Artemis Fowl II]] when he uncovers evidence of fairy existence. He demands one metric ton of gold as her ransom fund. When she consents to granting Artemis's wish of restoring his mother's sanity, he releases her along with half of her ransom fund. The rest of party try to Bio-bomb Fowl Manor, but realize that Artemis has escaped the McDonald's restaurant. Holly also then realizes that she is up for a challenge, and promises to be waiting for him, with \"a big gun and a strong hug.\"\n\n===In '' The Arctic Incident''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Arctic Incident]]'', Holly is sent to detain Artemis when he is a suspect in a [[Goblin (Artemis Fowl)|goblin]] uprising. But to her surprise the mud boy is innocent of this particular crime and has never traded with goblins. So she, along with Artemis, [[Mulch Diggums]], and Commander Julius Root are informed by [[Foaly]] that [[Opal Koboi]] and [[List of characters in Artemis Fowl#C|Briar Cudgeon]] are behind the uprising. They break into Koboi Laboratories, where Cudgeon is killed and Koboi is incapacitated. After the goblins are contained, she travels to Murmansk to rescue Artemis's father, as they previously agreed in return for Artemis's help in capturing Cudgeon and Koboi.\n\n===In ''The Eternity Code''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Eternity Code]]'', Artemis requests Holly's help to heal Domovoi Butler and retrieve his [[List of concepts in Artemis Fowl#C Cube|C Cube]] from American businessman [[Jon Spiro#Jon Spiro|Jon Spiro]]. Together with [[Mulch Diggums]], [[Juliet Butler]], and [[Foaly]] directing technological elements of the mission, they break into the Spiro Needle and retrieve the Cube. Artemis is mind wiped at the end of the mission under the directions of Julius Root.\n\n===In ''The Opal Deception''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Opal Deception]]'', Holly is with Commander Root, a paternal figure to her, when [[Opal Koboi]] kills him. She is subsequently framed for the Commander's death and is forced to flee from fairy authorities. She later collaborates with Artemis Fowl, Butler, and Mulch Diggums to expose Koboi and prevent her plans for destroying [[Fairy (Artemis Fowl)|fairy]] civilization. Koboi is locked up in a secure facility. At the end of the book, Holly resigns from the [[Lower Elements Police|LEP]].\n\n===In ''The Lost Colony''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Lost Colony]]'', Holly is working as a private detective since her resignation from the LEP, along with Mulch Diggums. Though it was not going well and now they are bounty hunters, which are considered even less trustworthy then the criminals they track. Holly is informed about the [[Demon (Artemis Fowl)|demon]] race, a species of fairy that left earth and are now inhabiting an island in Limbo between earth and time, and is recruited to [[Section Eight (Artemis Fowl)|Section Eight]], which monitors them. When it becomes apparent that Artemis has encountered a demon, they encounter Minerva Paradizo, another child genius who has managed to obtain a demon, and the deranged Billy Kong. Artemis and Holly, along with two demons, [[List of characters in Artemis Fowl#N|\u21161]] and [[List of characters in Artemis Fowl#Q|Qwan]], are forced to go to Hybras to save demon civilization. When they arrive back at Artemis and Holly's time, they find that three years have passed in their own dimension.\n\n===In ''The Time Paradox''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Time Paradox]]'', Artemis and Holly travel into the past to find the silky sifaka lemur, the only thing that can save [[Fowl family (Artemis Fowl)|Angeline Fowl]] from death by a fairy disease, Spelltropy. The pair are forced to outwit Artemis's younger self and Damon Kronski, president of the \"Extinctionists\" organization. They eventually encounter [[Opal Koboi]], who needs the silky sifaka lemur to increase her own power. In the novel, Holly kisses Artemis, and quickly attributes it to the effects of time travel as she is now an adolescent fairy.\n\n===In ''The Atlantis Complex''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Atlantis Complex]]'', Artemis is mentally ill; his dabbles with magic have resulted in his developing Atlantis Complex; a fairy disease equivalent to OCD and multiple-personality disorder. Atlantis Complex also gives the victim a large amount of paranoia. He arranges for Holly and her fairy companions to meet him at a glacier in Iceland. Later, however, when Artemis proceeds to demonstrate his invention- a means of curing global warming- outdoors, a hacked martian probe gone rogue descends and attacks the LEP ship on the glacier, killing several marines and Commander Raine Vinyaya, then heads towards Atlantis, the underwater fairy metropolis. Entangled in a conspiracy planned by Holly's old nemesis, the impending crisis and Artemis's rapid deterioration into a soppy alter-ego called Orion who perceives Holly as his 'fair princess' forces Holly to take the lead and find a way to bring back Artemis before it is too late.\n\n===In ''The Last Guardian''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Last Guardian]]'', Artemis' condition has improved, with he and Holly having formed a certain friendship with 'Nopal', the near-brain-dead clone of Opal Koboi. When Opal's plan for revenge results in her releasing ancient fairy guardians, Artemis is forced to apparently sacrifice himself and Nopal to stop her, but provides Holly with a sample of his DNA that she can use to clone a new body for his discorporated soul. As the series concludes, Holly is sharing her history with Artemis with his revived but amnesic self.\n\n===In ''The Fowl Twins''===\nIn ''The Fowl Twins''- a spin-off sequel series focusing on Artemis's younger brothers Myles and Beckett- Holly is revealed to have been promoted to Commodore, and also served as the (initially unknowing) template for NANNI, an artificial intelligence designed by Artemis and Myles to be the twins' guardian in the absence of the senior Fowls. She is also the mentor of Lieutenant Lazuli, a pixie-elf hybrid LEP officer who becomes associated with the Fowl twins during the crisis. At the conclusion of the novel, Lazuli is promoted to the position of head of the Fowl-fairy liaison office to maintain contact with the twins, after it is determined that the magic they retained following their possession by guardian spirits in ''Last Guardian'' legally qualifies them as magical creatures under fairy law.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Artemis Fowl II]]\n* [[Whitewashing in film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Holly Short.ogg|2008-11-13}}\n\n{{Artemis Fowl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Short, Holly}}\n[[Category:Artemis Fowl characters]]\n[[Category:Female characters in literature]]\n[[Category:Fictional elves]]\n[[Category:Fictional police officers]]\n[[Category:Fictional private investigators]]\n[[Category:Fictional bounty hunters]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 2001]]\n\n[[fr:Personnages de Artemis Fowl#Holly Short]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox character\n| name        = Holly Short\n| series      = [[Artemis Fowl]]\n| image       = HollyMediumCloseup.png\n| image_size  = 150px\n| caption     = Holly Short as depicted in ''[[Artemis Fowl: The Graphic Novel]]''\n| first       = ''[[Artemis Fowl (novel)|Artemis Fowl]]''\n| last        = ''[[The Fowl Twins]]''\n| creator     = [[Eoin Colfer]]\n| portrayer   = [[Lara McDonnell]]\n| species     = Elf\n| gender      = Female\n| occupation  = Captain of the [[Lower Elements Police#LEPrecon|LEPrecon]]<br>Commodore (''The Fowl Twins'')\n}}\n'''Captain Holly Short''' is a character of the ''[[Artemis Fowl]]'' novel series by [[Eoin Colfer]].\n\n==Character outline==\nHolly Short is a weird and quirky [[Elf (Artemis Fowl)|elf]] with an auburn [[crew cut]] (although she later grows a fringe) and 1 hazel and 1 blue eye, as well as the pointy ears typical of her species and nut-brown skin of a [[coffee]] complexion. She stands at one meter in height (said to be three feet in US editions), one centimeter shorter than the [[Fairy (Artemis Fowl)|fairy]] average (an inch shorter in US editions), and has a gymnast-like stance. Like all elves, she is child-sized by human standards, but her bodily proportions are adult. According to ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Arctic Incident]]'', Holly is about eighty years old (Elves and other magic species live much longer than humans. It is said that there is a dwarf over 2000 years old in the book).<ref name=\"Opal Deception\">{{cite book| last = Colfer| first = Eoin| title = Artemis Fowl and the Opal Deception| series = Artemis Fowl| date = 30 April 2005| publisher = Puffin Books| location = New York| isbn = 978-0-14-138164-0| page = 107| chapter = Narrow Escapes }}</ref> Holly is the first and only female captain in the organization [[Lower Elements Police#LEPrecon|LEPrecon]]. In ''[[The Artemis Fowl Files]]'', she notes that she eventually earns the respect of her male colleagues. Holly will defy the orders of superiors and disobey rules if she believes that she can be of more help that way, and has gotten into trouble multiple times for defying a direct command.<ref name=\"AFFiles\">{{cite book| last = Colfer| first = Eoin| title = The Artemis Fowl Files| series = Artemis Fowl| date = 2005-11-05| publisher = Hyperion Books for Children| location = New York| isbn = 978-1-4231-0044-7| pages = [https://archive.org/details/artmisfowlfiles00eoin/page/86 86\u201387]| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/artmisfowlfiles00eoin/page/86}}</ref> She is described as pretty, but in a dangerous way, comparable to a [[Latrodectus|black widow]]. Her interests include playing the fairy game \"Crunchball\", reading (especially thrillers), and flying with artificial wings.<ref name=\"AFFiles\" />\n\nHolly lost her father at a young age. Her mother, Coral Short, is described as a European elf who was temperamental and had an appearance similar to Holly's. ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Time Paradox]]'' reveals that her mother worked in [[Lower Elements Police]] division \"LEPmarine\" and died after she was exposed to dirty radiation, which is poisonous to fairies.<ref name=\"TimeParadox\">{{cite book|last=Colfer|first=Eoin|title=Artemis Fowl: The Time Paradox|url=https://archive.org/details/artemisfowltimep00colf|url-access=registration|publisher=Hyperion Books for Children|location=New York|date=July 2008|series=Artemis Fowl|pages=[https://archive.org/details/artemisfowltimep00colf/page/48 48\u201349]|isbn=978-1-4231-0836-8 }}</ref>\n\nAfter ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Opal Deception]]'', Holly quits the LEP because the new LEP commander, Ark Sool mentions that he will keep a close eye on her to catch any faults and she begins to work with [[Mulch Diggums]].\n\nHowever, after working as a private detective with Mulch for a short time, she returns to the Section 8 unit of the LEP in ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Lost Colony]]'', in time to get Artemis, Butler and the others out of trouble.\n\nHer relationship with Artemis Fowl has changed dramatically since the beginning of the series, morphing from hostility to grudging respect to friendship, and has recently included substantial hints of a romantic attraction despite the species and age gap (the mental age gap being closed in ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Lost Colony]]'' and physical age gap briefly being closed for ''Artemis Fowl and the The Time Paradox'', both via extensive [[time travel]]).\n\n==Appearances==\n===In ''Artemis Fowl''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl (novel)|Artemis Fowl]]'', Holly is abducted by 125-year-old criminal mastermind [[Artemis Fowl II]] when he uncovers evidence of fairy existence. He demands one metric ton of gold as her ransom fund. When she consents to granting Artemis's wish of restoring his mother's sanity, he releases her along with half of her ransom fund. The rest of party try to Bio-bomb Fowl Manor, but realize that Artemis has escaped the McDonald's resturant. Holly also then realizes that she is up for a challenge, and promises to be waiting for him, with \"a big gun and a strong hug.\"\n\n===In '' The Arctic Incident''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Arctic Incident]]'', Holly is sent to detain Artemis when he is a suspect in a [[Goblin (Artemis Fowl)|goblin]] uprising. But to her surprise the mud boy is innocent of this particular crime and has never traded with goblins. So she, along with Artemis, [[Mulch Diggums]], and Commander Julius Root are informed by [[Foaly]] that [[Opal Koboi]] and [[List of characters in Artemis Fowl#C|Briar Cudgeon]] are behind the uprising. They break into Koboi Laboratories, where Cudgeon is killed and Koboi is incapacitated. After the goblins are contained, she travels to Murmansk to rescue Artemis's father, as they previously agreed in return for Artemis's help in capturing Cudgeon and Koboi.\n\n===In ''The Eternity Code''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Eternity Code]]'', Artemis requests Holly's help to heal Domovoi Butler and retrieve his [[List of concepts in Artemis Fowl#C Cube|C Cube]] from American businessman [[Jon Spiro#Jon Spiro|Jon Spiro]]. Together with [[Mulch Diggums]], [[Juliet Butler]], and [[Foaly]] directing technological elements of the mission, they break into the Spiro Needle and retrieve the Cube. Artemis is mind wiped at the end of the mission under the directions of Julius Root.\n\n===In ''The Opal Deception''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Opal Deception]]'', Holly is with Commander Root, a paternal figure to her, when [[Opal Koboi]] kills him. She is subsequently framed for the Commander's death and is forced to flee from fairy authorities. She later collaborates with Artemis Fowl, Butler, and Mulch Diggums to expose Koboi and prevent her plans for destroying [[Fairy (Artemis Fowl)|fairy]] civilization. Koboi is locked up in a secure facility. At the end of the book, Holly resigns from the [[Lower Elements Police|LEP]].\n\n===In ''The Lost Colony''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Lost Colony]]'', Holly is working as a private detective since her resignation from the LEP, along with Mulch Diggums. Though it was not going well and now they are bounty hunters, which are considered even less trustworthy then the criminals they track. Holly is informed about the [[Demon (Artemis Fowl)|demon]] race, a species of fairy that left earth and are now inhabiting an island in Limbo between earth and time, and is recruited to [[Section Eight (Artemis Fowl)|Section Eight]], which monitors them. When it becomes apparent that Artemis has encountered a demon, they encounter Minerva Paradizo, another child genius who has managed to obtain a demon, and the deranged Billy Kong. Artemis and Holly, along with two demons, [[List of characters in Artemis Fowl#N|\u21161]] and [[List of characters in Artemis Fowl#Q|Qwan]], are forced to go to Hybras to save demon civilization. When they arrive back at Artemis and Holly's time, they find that three years have passed in their own dimension.\n\n===In ''The Time Paradox''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Time Paradox]]'', Artemis and Holly travel into the past to find the silky sifaka lemur, the only thing that can save [[Fowl family (Artemis Fowl)|Angeline Fowl]] from death by a fairy disease, Spelltropy. The pair are forced to outwit Artemis's younger self and Damon Kronski, president of the \"Extinctionists\" organization. They eventually encounter [[Opal Koboi]], who needs the silky sifaka lemur to increase her own power. In the novel, Holly kisses Artemis, and quickly attributes it to the effects of time travel as she is now an adolescent fairy.\n\n===In ''The Atlantis Complex''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Atlantis Complex]]'', Artemis is mentally ill; his dabbles with magic have resulted in his developing Atlantis Complex; a fairy disease equivalent to OCD and multiple-personality disorder. Atlantis Complex also gives the victim a large amount of paranoia. He arranges for Holly and her fairy companions to meet him at a glacier in Iceland. Later, however, when Artemis proceeds to demonstrate his invention- a means of curing global warming- outdoors, a hacked martian probe gone rogue descends and attacks the LEP ship on the glacier, killing several marines and Commander Raine Vinyaya, then heads towards Atlantis, the underwater fairy metropolis. Entangled in a conspiracy planned by Holly's old nemesis, the impending crisis and Artemis's rapid deterioration into a soppy alter-ego called Orion who perceives Holly as his 'fair princess' forces Holly to take the lead and find a way to bring back Artemis before it is too late.\n\n===In ''The Last Guardian''===\nIn ''[[Artemis Fowl and the Last Guardian]]'', Artemis' condition has improved, with he and Holly having formed a certain friendship with 'Nopal', the near-brain-dead clone of Opal Koboi. When Opal's plan for revenge results in her releasing ancient fairy guardians, Artemis is forced to apparently sacrifice himself and Nopal to stop her, but provides Holly with a sample of his DNA that she can use to clone a new body for his discorporated soul. As the series concludes, Holly is sharing her history with Artemis with his revived but amnesic self.\n\n===In ''The Fowl Twins''===\nIn ''The Fowl Twins''- a spin-off sequel series focusing on Artemis's younger brothers Myles and Beckett- Holly is revealed to have been promoted to Commodore, and also served as the (initially unknowing) template for NANNI, an artificial intelligence designed by Artemis and Myles to be the twins' guardian in the absence of the senior Fowls. She is also the mentor of Lieutenant Lazuli, a pixie-elf hybrid LEP officer who becomes associated with the Fowl twins during the crisis. At the conclusion of the novel, Lazuli is promoted to the position of head of the Fowl-fairy liaison office to maintain contact with the twins, after it is determined that the magic they retained following their possession by guardian spirits in ''Last Guardian'' legally qualifies them as magical creatures under fairy law.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Artemis Fowl II]]\n* [[Whitewashing in film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Holly Short.ogg|2008-11-13}}\n\n{{Artemis Fowl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Short, Holly}}\n[[Category:Artemis Fowl characters]]\n[[Category:Female characters in literature]]\n[[Category:Fictional elves]]\n[[Category:Fictional police officers]]\n[[Category:Fictional private investigators]]\n[[Category:Fictional bounty hunters]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 2001]]\n\n[[fr:Personnages de Artemis Fowl#Holly Short]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holly_Short"}
