g|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 14-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|35.4|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was destroyed by fire at the mouth of [[Pat Creek]] ({{coord|56|20|30|N|132|20|20|W|name=Pat Creek}}) in [[Southeast Alaska]] near [[Wrangell, Alaska|Wrangell]], [[Territory of Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwrecksa>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-a/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (A)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Douro||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=The coaster collided in the [[Mediterranean]] with {{SS|Drago||2}} ({{flag|Spain|1945}}) and sank.<ref name=Times120254>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Telegrams in Brief |day_of_week=Friday |date=12 February 1954 |page_number=7 |issue=52854 |column=G }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===12 February===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=12 February 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Daun Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Japan}}\n|desc=The [[Coastal trading vessel|coaster]] sank off [[Honshu]], [[Japan]], with the loss of 16 of her 25 crew.<ref name=Times130254>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Telegrams in Brief |day_of_week=Saturday |date=13 February 1954 |page_number=5 |issue=52855 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mildred''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 12-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|50|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was destroyed by fire {{convert|1.5|nmi}} northeast of [[East Point (Alaska)|East Point]] ({{coord|56|23|00|N|132|24|20|W|name=East Point}}) on [[Woronkofski Island]] in the [[Alexander Archipelago]] in [[Southeast Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwrecksm>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-m/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (M)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===13 February===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=13 February 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[List of Empire ships - Sa to Sh#Empire Seablue|''Seablue'']] \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The coaster struck the wreck of ''[[Empire Blessing]]'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and was holed. An attempt was made to beach her but she sank near [[Vlissingen]], [[Netherlands]]. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===19 February===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=19 February 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Danubian||2}} \n|flag={{Flag|Panama}}\n|desc=The cargo ship struck rocks at the [[Black Sea]] entrance to the [[Bosphorus]] and sank.<ref name=Times200254>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=News in Brief |day_of_week=Saturday |date=20 February 1954 |page_number=5 |issue=52861 |column=D }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===24 February===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=24 February 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Holger Danske||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Denmark}}\n|desc=The [[icebreaker]] collided with the [[ferry]] {{SS|Broen||2}} ({{flag|Denmark}}) in Nyborg Firth and ran aground. Two of her crew were killed.<ref name=Times250254>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ice Breaker Aground After Collision |day_of_week=Thursday |date=25 February 1954 |page_number=6 |issue=52865 |column=C }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===27 February===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=27 February 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Crown No. 2'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 1,295-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|260|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[scow]] was wrecked near [[Tree Point]] ({{coord|54|48|15|N|130|55|45|W|name=Tree Point}}) in [[Southeast Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwrecksc>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-c/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (C)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==March==\n\n===1 March===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 March 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Captain Antonios K||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Costa Rica}}\n|desc=The cargo ship sank in the Mediterranean Sea ({{coord|37|05|N|07|53|E}}). All 15 crew rescued by {{SS|Nigaristan||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=Antonios>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?158503 |title=SS Captain Antonios K. (+1954) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=Times020354>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Telegrams in Brief |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=2 March 1954 |page_number=6 |issue=52869 |column=E }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===8 March===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=8 March 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Zongdulak||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Turkey}}\n|desc=The cargo ship collided with {{SS|Yolac Port||2}} ({{flag|Turkey}}) in the [[Black Sea]] and sank. All crew rescued by ''Yolac Port''.<ref name=Times090354>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Loss Of Turkis Ship |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=5 March 1954 |page_number=5 |issue=52875 |column=G }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===10 March===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=10 March 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|ST|Fenman||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The [[tugboat|tug]] capsized and sank whilst assisting the berthing of {{SS|Rudolf||2}} ({{flag|Sweden}}) at [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]]. Three of her four crew were killed.<ref name=Times110354>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Tug Overturned While Berthing Ship |day_of_week=Thursday |date=11 March 1954 |page_number=2 |issue=58277 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Guildford||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The collier collided with another ship and then went aground at the mouth of the [[river Tees|Tees]]. Salvage attempts abandoned in May and the wreck was blown up on 26 August 1955.<ref name=Guildford>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?11605 |title=MV Guildford (+1954) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=Times130554>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=News in Brief |day_of_week=