r The Times |articlename=Spanish Minesweeper Lost In Gale |day_of_week=Saturday |date=27 March 1954 |page_number=6 |issue=52891 |column=C }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===30 March===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=30 March 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Empire Windrush||2}} \n|flag={{Flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The [[ocean liner]] sank in the Mediterranean Sea following an explosion and fire in the engine room on 29 March. All passengers and crew rescued apart from the four killed in the explosion. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==April==\n\n===7 April===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 April 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Francescu||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Italy|civil}}\n|desc=The cargo ship ran aground in the [[Scheldt]], Belgium and broke in two.<ref name=Times080454>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Italian Ship Breaks In Two |day_of_week=Thursday |date=8 April 1954 |page_number=5 |issue=52901 |column=B }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===15 April===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=15 April 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Chelan'' \n|flag={{flag|Canada|1868}}\n|desc=While [[towing]] a [[barge]] from [[Skagway, Alaska|Skagway]], [[Territory of Alaska]], to [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]], the 541-ton, {{convert|154|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[Tugboat|tug]] sank off the entrance to [[Sumner Strait]] approximately {{convert|4|nmi}} west of [[Cape Decision Light|Cape Decision]] in [[Southeast Alaska]] with the loss of all 14 people aboard. Only two bodies were recovered. Her wreck was found in June 1979, but plans to [[Marine salvage|salvage]] her were abandoned.<ref name=alaskashipwrecksc>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-c/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (C)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unidentified barge \n|flag=flag unknown\n|desc=While under [[Towing|tow]] from [[Skagway, Alaska|Skagway]], [[Territory of Alaska]], to [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]], with a cargo of [[silver]], [[lead]], and [[zinc]] [[ore concentrate]]s by the [[Tugboat|tug]] ''Chelan'' ({{flag|Canada|1868}}), the {{convert|240|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[barge]] \u2013 formerly the [[Passenger ship|passenger]] [[Steamship|steamer]] {{SS|Princess Mary}} ({{flag|Canada|1868}}) \u2013 was lost after ''Chelan'' sank off the entrance to [[Sumner Strait]] approximately {{convert|4|nmi}} west of [[Cape Decision Light|Cape Decision]] in [[Southeast Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwrecksc>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-c/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (C)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===18 April===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=18 April 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|HM Minesweeper|1558}} \n|flag={{flagicon|United Kingdom|naval}} [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]]\n|desc=The minesweeper caught fire and sank in the [[English Channel]] off [[Ostend]], Belgium. All 31 crew rescued by the steamship ''Phoenix'' ({{flag|Netherlands}}) and {{SS|Tunisie||2}} ({{flag|France}}).<ref name=Times190454>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Rescued Crew's Return |day_of_week=Monday |date=19 April 1954 |page_number=4 |issue=52909 |column=A }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==May==\n===2 May===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date= 2 May 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''A F L 1654'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 1,007-[[gross register ton]] [[barge]] was wrecked on the coast of [[Montague Island (Alaska)|Montague Island]] off the [[Southcentral Alaska|south-central]] coast of the [[Territory of Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwrecksa>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-a/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (A)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===9 May===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date= 9 May 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sinbad''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 9-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|32.6|ft|m|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] sank at [[Gravina Point]] ({{coord|60|37|30|N|146|15|00|W|name=Gravina Point}}) in [[Prince William Sound]] on the south-central coast of the [[Territory of Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwreckss>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-s/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (S)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===10 May===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=10 May 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tatsuwa Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Japan}}\n|desc=The cargo ship sprang a leak {{convert|500|nmi|km}} west of [[Manila]], Philippines. Presumed to have foundered with the loss of all 50 crew.<ref name=Times091054>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Freighter Lost With Crew Of 50 |day_of_week=Saturday |date=9 October 1954 |page_number=6 |issue=53058 |column=C }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===11 May===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=11 May 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Topaze|1933|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Belgium}}\n|desc=The cargo ship was wrecked. Scrapped later that month.<ref name=BelgePZ/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===14 May===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=14 May 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|ST|Harrington||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The tug capsized and sank at [[Swansea]], [[Glamorgan]], with the loss of two of her six crew.<ref name=Times140554>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Tug Sinks In Swansea Dock |day_of_week=Saturday |date=15 May 1954 |page_number=3 |issue=52932 |columnC= }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===15 May===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date= 15 May 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Loyal''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 11-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|36.9|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was destroyed by fire in [[Kimshan Cove]] ({{coord|57|41|20|N|136|07|00|W|name=Kimshan Cove}}) in [[Southeast Alaska]].<ref name