r 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|ROCS|Tai Ping}} \n|flag={{nowrap begin}}{{navy|Republic of China}}{{nowrap end}}\n|desc=[[Chinese Civil War]]: The [[Evarts-class destroyer escort|''Tai Kang''-class destroyer escort]] was torpedoed and sunk off the [[Tachen Islands]] by the [[motor torpedo boat]]s {{ship|Chinese motor torpedo boat|No. 155||2}}, {{ship|Chinese motor torpedo boat|No. 156||2}}, {{ship|Chinese motor torpedo boat|No. 157||2}}, {{ship|Chinese motor torpedo boat|No. 158||2}} (all {{navy|China}}) with the loss of 40 of her crew of about 200.<ref name=Times151154>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Chinese Nationalist Warship Sunk |day_of_week=Monday |date=15 November 1954 |page_number=8 |issue=53089 |column=D }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=50411 |title=Chinese Naval Battles (Civil War and later)|accessdate=6 February 2018}}</ref><ref>Gray, Randal, ed., ''Conway\u2032s All the World\u2032s Fighting Ships 1947\u20131982, Part II: The Warsaw Pact and Non-Aligned Nations'', Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1983, ISBN 0-87021-919-7, p. 327.</ref>\n }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===15 November===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=15 November 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Barracuda'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 17-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|40|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] sank in [[Southeast Alaska]] between [[Onslow Island]] ({{coord|55|52|30|N|132|22|00|W|name=Onslow Island}}) and [[Split Island (Alaska)|Split Island]] ({{coord|55.9506|N|132.4547|W|name=Split Island}}).<ref name=alaskashipwrecksb>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-b/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (B)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===26 November===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=26 November 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Carpo||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=The coaster sank off [[The Lizard]], [[Cornwall]], United Kingdom with the loss of all twelve crew.<ref name=Times301154/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===27 November===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=27 November 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''[[South Goodwin Lightship]]'' \n|flag={{Flag|United Kingdom|government}}\n|desc=Capsized on the [[Goodwin Sands]] with the loss of all seven crewmen. The only survivor was a [[Ministry of Agriculture]] scientist who had been on board bird-watching.<ref name=Weather>{{cite book|author1=Bob Ogley |author2=Ian Currie |author3=Mark Davison |year=1991|title=The Kent Weather Book|page=88|publisher=Froglets Publications Ltd|location=Brasted Chart|isbn=1-872337-35-X}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|World Concord||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Liberia}}\n|desc=The tanker broke in two in the [[Irish Sea]]. Both halves towed to the [[River Clyde|Clyde]].<ref name=Times301154/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===28 November===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date= 28 November 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''KFC-8''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 9-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|30|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was destroyed by fire near [[Afognak, Alaska|Afognak]], [[Territory of Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwrecksk>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-k/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (K)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===29 November===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=29 November 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Gustav||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Finland}}\n|desc=The coaster was reported to be listing severely {{convert|20|nmi|km}} north east of the [[Channel Islands]].<ref name=Times301154>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Search For Finnish Vessel |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=30 November 1954 |page_number=8 |issue=53102 |column=C }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===30 November===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=30 November 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Tresillian||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The cargo ship foundered in [[St George's Channel]], {{convert|44|nmi|km}} off [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Ireland with the loss of 24 of her 40 crew. Sixteen survivors rescued by {{SS|Liparus||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and transferred to {{ship|L\u00c9|Maev|02|6}} ({{navy|Republic of Ireland}}) and landed at [[Cobh]].<ref name=Times011254>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=16 Saved From Sunken Ship |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=1 December 1954 |page_number=8 |issue=53103 |column=E }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==December==\n===12 December===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=12 December 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Western Sun'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 79-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|68.7|ft|m|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was stranded and lost near the mouth of [[Kah Sheets Bay]] ({{coord|56|31|N|133|06|W|name=Kah Sheets Bay}}) at the south end of [[Duncan Canal (Alaska)|Duncan Canal]] in the [[Alexander Archipelago]] in [[Southeast Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwrecksw>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-w/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (W)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===15 December===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=15 December 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Talent|P337|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[British T-class submarine|T-class]] [[submarine]] was swept out of her dock at [[HMNB Chatham]] when a caisson collapsed. She ended up aground in the [[River Medway|Medway]]. Four people were killed. Later repaired and returned to service. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===18 December===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=18 December 1954 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Hispania|1912|2}} \n|flag={{Flag|Sweden}}\n|desc=Struck a rock in the Sound of Mull and sank with the loss of her captain. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n===20 December===\n{{shipwreck list begin |date= 20 December 1954 |